var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"location":"#FrontIntrinsicOps.jl-—-Documentation","page":"Home","title":"FrontIntrinsicOps.jl — Documentation","text":"FrontIntrinsicOps.jl is a static-surface PDE toolkit for triangulated front meshes. It implements intrinsic geometry, discrete exterior calculus (DEC), and a full suite of PDE solvers — all working directly on the surface without embedding into a bulk domain.\n\nRelease summary for ambient signed distance is available in CHANGELOG.md (v0.5 section).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"#Contents","page":"Home","title":"Contents","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Mathematical-Background","page":"Home","title":"Mathematical Background","text":"Detailed derivations and formulas for every module:\n\nDocument Topic\nMesh types and data structures CurveMesh, SurfaceMesh, and the primal–dual picture\nTopology and incidence matrices Edges, faces, orientation, d_0, d_1\nDiscrete geometry and dual areas Normals, areas, edge lengths, barycentric and mixed duals\nDiscrete exterior calculus Hodge stars, exterior derivatives, cochains\nLaplace–Beltrami operator DEC and cotan formulations, sign convention\nCurvature Signed (curve), mean, Gaussian, Gauss–Bonnet\nSurface diffusion, Poisson, Helmholtz Implicit time integration, gauge treatment\nScalar transport Conservative DEC fluxes, SSP-RK2/3, CFL\nAdvection–diffusion IMEX Splitting, stability, factory reuse\nReaction–diffusion IMEX θ-scheme, Fisher–KPP, bistable\nTangential vector calculus Projection, surface gradient/divergence, Whitney forms\nHodge decomposition Helmholtz–Hodge, harmonic forms, genus-g\nHigh-resolution transport Minmod, van Leer, superbee, SSP-RK2\nOpen surfaces and boundary conditions Boundary detection, Dirichlet, Neumann\nCaching and performance SurfacePDECache, in-place buffers, zero-allocation kernels\nMesh generators UV-sphere, icosphere, torus, ellipsoid, perturbed sphere\nAmbient signed distance Exact point-to-front distance, pseudonormal vs winding sign","category":"section"},{"location":"#API-Reference","page":"Home","title":"API Reference","text":"Concise function signatures and descriptions:\n\nDocument Module\nTypes CurveMesh, SurfaceMesh, SurfaceGeometry, …\nGenerators generate_icosphere, generate_torus, generate_ellipsoid, …\nGeometry and DEC compute_geometry, build_dec, Hodge stars\nPDE solvers Diffusion, transport, reaction–diffusion, open surfaces\nDiagnostics check_mesh, check_dec, Gauss–Bonnet, star1_sign_report\nPlotting with Makie Optional weak-extension plotting for CurveMesh / SurfaceMesh","category":"section"},{"location":"#Tutorials","page":"Home","title":"Tutorials","text":"Step-by-step worked examples:\n\nDocument Topic\nGetting started Sphere geometry in five lines\nSurface diffusion Heat equation on the sphere\nScalar transport Rotating a patch with SSP-RK3\nReaction–diffusion Fisher–KPP wave on the sphere\nHodge decomposition Decomposing a 1-form on sphere and torus\nOpen surfaces Poisson with Dirichlet BC on a cap\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"#Quick-reference","page":"Home","title":"Quick reference","text":"using FrontIntrinsicOps\n\n# ── Build mesh ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nmesh = generate_icosphere(1.0, 3)          # level-3 icosphere (~640 verts)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)              # intrinsic geometry\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)               # DEC operators\n\n# ── Geometry diagnostics ────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nprintln(\"Area   = \", measure(mesh, geom))\nprintln(\"χ      = \", euler_characteristic(mesh))\nprintln(\"GB res = \", gauss_bonnet_residual(mesh, geom))\n\n# ── Surface diffusion ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nu, fac = step_surface_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u0, dt, μ)\n\n# ── Reaction–diffusion (Fisher–KPP) ─────────────────────────────────────────\ncache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=0.1, dt=1e-3, θ=1.0)\nreaction = fisher_kpp_reaction(2.0)\nfor _ in 1:200; step_diffusion_cached!(u, cache, reaction, t); end\n\n# ── Hodge decomposition ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nα = dec.d0 * u\nresult = hodge_decompose_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α)\n# result.exact  result.coexact  result.harmonic\n\n# ── High-resolution transport ────────────────────────────────────────────────\nT_new = step_surface_transport_limited(mesh, geom, dec, topo, T, vel, dt;\n                                       limiter=:van_leer, method=:ssprk2)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"#Design-principles","page":"Home","title":"Design principles","text":"Discrete exterior calculus first — all operators derive from the primal cochain complex Omega^0 xrightarrowd_0 Omega^1 xrightarrowd_1 Omega^2.\nNo bulk-solver coupling — purely intrinsic; coupling lives in a separate package.\nSparse matrices throughout — every global operator is a SparseMatrixCSC.\nReuse factorizations — linear solves are the bottleneck; the cache layer amortizes factorization cost across many time steps.\nFloat64 default — parameterised on T<:AbstractFloat; Float32 meshes work.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"#License","page":"Home","title":"License","text":"MIT","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#API:-Types","page":"API Documentation","title":"API: Types","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#CurveMesh{T}","page":"API Documentation","title":"CurveMesh{T}","text":"Closed or open 2-D polygonal curve.\n\nCurveMesh{T <: AbstractFloat}\n  points :: Vector{SVector{2,T}}    # vertex coordinates (2-D)\n  edges  :: Vector{Tuple{Int,Int}}  # ordered edge list\n  closed :: Bool                    # whether the last edge closes to vertex 1\n\nConstructor: Load from file or build analytically via sample_circle.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#SurfaceMesh{T}","page":"API Documentation","title":"SurfaceMesh{T}","text":"Triangulated surface in mathbbR^3.\n\nSurfaceMesh{T <: AbstractFloat}\n  points :: Vector{SVector{3,T}}          # vertex positions\n  faces  :: Vector{Tuple{Int,Int,Int}}    # triangle indices (1-based)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#PointFront1D{T}","page":"API Documentation","title":"PointFront1D{T}","text":"Minimal 1-D front on a line (standalone from mesh/DEC machinery).\n\nPointFront1D{T <: Real}\n  x                  :: Vector{T}  # marker positions (length 1 or 2)\n  interval_is_inside :: Bool\n\nSemantics:\n\nlength(x) == 1:\ninterval_is_inside=true: inside is to the right (x >= xΓ)\ninterval_is_inside=false: inside is to the left (x <= xΓ)\nlength(x) == 2 with strict ordering x[1] < x[2]:\ninterval_is_inside=true: inside is [x[1], x[2]]\ninterval_is_inside=false: inside is the exterior of [x[1], x[2]]\n\nInvariants are validated at construction (1 or 2 markers only, finite coordinates, strict ordering for two markers).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#CurveGeometry{T}","page":"API Documentation","title":"CurveGeometry{T}","text":"Pre-computed intrinsic geometry of a CurveMesh.\n\nCurveGeometry{T}\n  edge_lengths         :: Vector{T}\n  edge_tangents        :: Vector{SVector{2,T}}\n  vertex_dual_lengths  :: Vector{T}\n  vertex_normals       :: Vector{SVector{2,T}}\n  signed_curvature     :: Vector{T}\n\nBuild with compute_geometry(mesh::CurveMesh).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#SurfaceGeometry{T}","page":"API Documentation","title":"SurfaceGeometry{T}","text":"Pre-computed intrinsic geometry of a SurfaceMesh.\n\nSurfaceGeometry{T}\n  face_normals          :: Vector{SVector{3,T}}\n  face_areas            :: Vector{T}\n  edge_lengths          :: Vector{T}\n  vertex_dual_areas     :: Vector{T}\n  vertex_normals        :: Vector{SVector{3,T}}\n  mean_curvature        :: Vector{T}      # filled by compute_curvature!\n  gaussian_curvature    :: Vector{T}      # filled by compute_curvature!\n  dual_area_method      :: Symbol         # :barycentric or :mixed\n\nBuild with compute_geometry(mesh::SurfaceMesh; dual_area=:barycentric).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#CurveDEC{T}","page":"API Documentation","title":"CurveDEC{T}","text":"Assembled DEC operators for a CurveMesh.\n\nCurveDEC{T}\n  d0         :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_E × N_V  coboundary\n  star0      :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_V × N_V  diagonal (dual lengths)\n  star1      :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_E × N_E  diagonal (edge/dual-length ratio)\n  laplacian  :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_V × N_V  Laplace–Beltrami (= -Δ)\n\nBuild with build_dec(mesh::CurveMesh, geom::CurveGeometry).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#SurfaceDEC{T}","page":"API Documentation","title":"SurfaceDEC{T}","text":"Assembled DEC operators for a SurfaceMesh.\n\nSurfaceDEC{T}\n  d0         :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_E × N_V\n  d1         :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_F × N_E\n  star0      :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_V × N_V  diagonal (dual areas)\n  star1      :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_E × N_E  diagonal (cotan weights)\n  star2      :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_F × N_F  diagonal (inverse face areas)\n  laplacian  :: SparseMatrixCSC   # N_V × N_V  Laplace–Beltrami\n\nBuild with build_dec(mesh::SurfaceMesh, geom::SurfaceGeometry; laplace=:dec).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#MeshTopology","page":"API Documentation","title":"MeshTopology","text":"Topological adjacency lists derived from a SurfaceMesh.\n\nMeshTopology\n  edges            :: Vector{Tuple{Int,Int}}    # canonical (i<j) edge list\n  edge_index       :: Dict{Tuple{Int,Int},Int}  # fast lookup\n  face_edges       :: Vector{Vector{Int}}       # face → 3 edge indices\n  face_edge_signs  :: Vector{Vector{Int}}       # ±1 orientation signs\n  vertex_faces     :: Vector{Vector{Int}}       # vertex → adjacent faces\n  vertex_edges     :: Vector{Vector{Int}}       # vertex → adjacent edges\n  edge_faces       :: Vector{Vector{Int}}       # edge → 1 or 2 faces\n\nBuild with build_topology(mesh::SurfaceMesh).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#SurfacePDECache{T}","page":"API Documentation","title":"SurfacePDECache{T}","text":"Pre-assembled PDE operators and factorizations for fast repeated solves.\n\nSurfacePDECache{T}\n  dec          :: SurfaceDEC\n  mass         :: SparseMatrixCSC   # M = star0\n  laplacian    :: SparseMatrixCSC   # L\n  system       :: SparseMatrixCSC   # (M + dt θ μ L)\n  factorization                     # sparse LU or Cholesky\n  μ            :: T\n  dt           :: T\n  θ            :: T\n\nBuild with build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ, dt, θ).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#SurfaceDiffusionBuffers{T}-and-SurfaceRDBuffers{T}","page":"API Documentation","title":"SurfaceDiffusionBuffers{T} and SurfaceRDBuffers{T}","text":"Pre-allocated scratch buffers for zero-allocation time steps.\n\nSurfaceDiffusionBuffers{T}\n  rhs :: Vector{T}\n  tmp :: Vector{T}\n\nSurfaceRDBuffers{T}\n  rhs      :: Vector{T}\n  reaction :: Vector{T}\n  tmp      :: Vector{T}\n\nBuild with alloc_diffusion_buffers(nv) or alloc_rd_buffers(nv).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#See-also","page":"API Documentation","title":"See also","text":"Mesh types (math)\nDiscrete exterior calculus (math)\nCaching and performance (math)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#Ambient-signed-distance-API-(v0.5)","page":"API Documentation","title":"Ambient signed-distance API (v0.5)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#build_signed_distance_cache","page":"API Documentation","title":"build_signed_distance_cache","text":"build_signed_distance_cache(mesh; leafsize=8) -> SignedDistanceCache\n\nBuilds an exact nearest-primitive acceleration cache (AABB tree + sign data) for CurveMesh and SurfaceMesh.","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#signed_distance-(batched)","page":"API Documentation","title":"signed_distance (batched)","text":"signed_distance(points, mesh_or_cache;\n                sign_mode=:auto,\n                lower_bound=0.0,\n                upper_bound=Inf,\n                return_normals=true)\n\nAccepted points formats:\n\nVector{SVector{N,T}}\nMatrix{T} with shape (N,np) or (np,N)\n\nReturns (S, I, C, N):\n\nS: signed distances,\nI: closest primitive ids,\nC: closest points,\nN: signing normals (pseudonormal mode).","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#signed_distance-(scalar)","page":"API Documentation","title":"signed_distance (scalar)","text":"signed_distance(point::SVector{N,T}, mesh_or_cache; sign_mode=:auto)\n\nReturns named tuple (distance, primitive, closest, normal).","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#unsigned_distance","page":"API Documentation","title":"unsigned_distance","text":"unsigned_distance(points, mesh_or_cache)\n\nConvenience wrapper for signed_distance(...; sign_mode=:unsigned).","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#winding_number","page":"API Documentation","title":"winding_number","text":"winding_number(point, mesh_or_cache)\n\nClosed 2D curve: integer winding number.\nClosed 3D oriented surface: normalized solid-angle winding number.","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#is_closed_curve-and-is_closed_surface","page":"API Documentation","title":"is_closed_curve and is_closed_surface","text":"is_closed_curve(mesh::CurveMesh) -> Bool\nis_closed_surface(mesh::SurfaceMesh) -> Bool\n\nClosure predicates used by sign_mode=:auto.","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#1-D-point-front-signed-distance","page":"API Documentation","title":"1-D point-front signed distance","text":"signed_distance(front::PointFront1D, x::Real)\nsigned_distance(front::PointFront1D, xs::AbstractVector)\nrebuild_signed_distance(front::PointFront1D, xnodes::AbstractVector)\ninterface_normals(front::PointFront1D)\n\nSign convention is the same: negative inside, positive outside, zero on marker(s).","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#Open-mesh-sign-semantics","page":"API Documentation","title":"Open-mesh sign semantics","text":"Closed meshes with sign_mode=:winding provide inside/outside sign.\nOpen meshes with sign_mode=:pseudonormal provide oriented side sign.\nOpen meshes do not define a global inside/outside region.\nIn :pseudonormal mode, points on the front return distance 0.\nNear ambiguous configurations (signing dot-product within tolerance), the sign can evaluate to 0.","category":"section"},{"location":"types/#Short-examples","page":"API Documentation","title":"Short examples","text":"Closed 2D curve:\n\nmesh = sample_circle(1.0, 128)\ncache = build_signed_distance_cache(mesh)\nr_in  = signed_distance(SVector(0.0, 0.0), cache; sign_mode=:winding)\nr_out = signed_distance(SVector(2.0, 0.0), cache; sign_mode=:winding)\n# r_in.distance < 0, r_out.distance > 0\n\nOpen 2D curve:\n\nmesh = load_curve_points([SVector(-1.0, 0.0), SVector(1.0, 0.0)]; closed=false)\ncache = build_signed_distance_cache(mesh)\nr_up = signed_distance(SVector(0.0, 0.5), cache; sign_mode=:pseudonormal)\nr_dn = signed_distance(SVector(0.0, -0.5), cache; sign_mode=:pseudonormal)\n# opposite signs across the oriented curve\n\nClosed 3D surface:\n\nmesh = generate_icosphere(1.0, 2)\ncache = build_signed_distance_cache(mesh)\nr_in  = signed_distance(SVector(0.0, 0.0, 0.0), cache; sign_mode=:winding)\nr_out = signed_distance(SVector(2.0, 0.0, 0.0), cache; sign_mode=:winding)\n# r_in.distance < 0, r_out.distance > 0\n\nOpen 3D patch:\n\npts = [SVector(0.0,0.0,0.0), SVector(1.0,0.0,0.0), SVector(1.0,1.0,0.0), SVector(0.0,1.0,0.0)]\nfaces = [SVector(1,2,3), SVector(1,3,4)]\nmesh = SurfaceMesh{Float64}(pts, faces)\ncache = build_signed_distance_cache(mesh)\nr_top = signed_distance(SVector(0.5,0.5,0.3), cache; sign_mode=:pseudonormal)\nr_bot = signed_distance(SVector(0.5,0.5,-0.3), cache; sign_mode=:pseudonormal)\n# opposite signs across the oriented sheet","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Hodge-Decomposition-of-1-Forms","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Hodge Decomposition of 1-Forms","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Overview","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Overview","text":"The Hodge–Helmholtz decomposition (or Hodge decomposition) states that every smooth 1-form alpha on a compact Riemannian manifold can be uniquely decomposed as:\n\nalpha = dphi + deltapsi + h\n\nwhere:\n\ndphi = nabla_Gamma phi\nis the exact component (gradient of a potential phi),\ndeltapsi = star d star psi\nis the coexact component (codifferential of a potential psi),\nh\nis the harmonic component (dh = 0, delta h = 0).\n\nThe dimension of the harmonic space equals the first Betti number b_1 = 2g, where g is the genus of the surface:\n\nSurface Genus g b_1 Harmonic forms\nSphere 0 0 None (trivial harmonic space)\nTorus 1 2 Two independent harmonic 1-forms\nGenus-g surface g 2g 2g independent harmonic 1-forms\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Discrete-Hodge-decomposition","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Discrete Hodge decomposition","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Step-1:-Exact-component","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Step 1: Exact component","text":"Solve the scalar Poisson equation for phi:\n\nL phi = delta_1 alpha = star_0^-1 d_0^top star_1 alpha\n\n(the codifferential of alpha), then set alpha_textexact = d_0 phi.\n\nOn a closed surface L is singular; the Tikhonov regularisation (L + varepsilon I) phi = delta_1 alpha is used.","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Step-2:-Coexact-component","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Step 2: Coexact component","text":"Solve the dual Poisson equation for psi:\n\ntildeL psi = d_1 alpha\n\nwhere tildeL = star_2^-1 d_1 star_1^-1 d_1^top star_2 is the Laplacian on 2-forms (equivalently, on dual 0-cochains).\n\nSet alpha_textcoexact = delta_2 (star_2 psi) = star_1^-1 d_1^top star_2 psi.","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Step-3:-Harmonic-residual","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Step 3: Harmonic residual","text":"h = alpha - alpha_textexact - alpha_textcoexact\n\nFor a genus-0 surface (sphere) h approx 0 (up to numerical error). For a torus h captures the two independent topological cycles.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#API","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"API","text":"# Full decomposition\nresult = hodge_decompose_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α; reg=1e-10)\n# result.exact       Vector{T}  — α_exact  = d0 φ\n# result.coexact     Vector{T}  — α_coexact = δ₂(⋆₂ ψ)\n# result.harmonic    Vector{T}  — h = α - α_exact - α_coexact\n# result.phi         Vector{T}  — scalar potential φ\n# result.psi         Vector{T}  — stream potential ψ\n\n# Individual components\nα_exact,   φ = exact_component_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α)\nα_coexact, ψ = coexact_component_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α)\nh              = harmonic_component_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Diagnostics","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Diagnostics","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Reconstruction-residual","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Reconstruction residual","text":"r = fracalpha - alpha_textexact - alpha_textcoexact - h_star_1alpha_star_1\n\nwhere the star_1-norm is cdot_star_1^2 = alpha^top star_1 alpha.\n\nr = hodge_decomposition_residual(mesh, geom, dec, α, result)\n# r ≈ 0 (machine precision) by definition","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Orthogonality-check","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Orthogonality check","text":"The three components should be mutually orthogonal in L^2:\n\nlangle alpha_textexact alpha_textcoexact rangle_star_1 approx 0\n\nlangle alpha_textexact h rangle_star_1 approx 0\n\nlangle alpha_textcoexact h rangle_star_1 approx 0\n\nips = hodge_inner_products(mesh, geom, dec, result)\n# ips.exact_coexact   ≈ 0\n# ips.exact_harmonic  ≈ 0\n# ips.coexact_harmonic ≈ 0\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Physical-interpretation","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Physical interpretation","text":"Component Geometry Physics\nalpha_textexact = dphi Gradient field, curl-free Conservative force, electric field\nalpha_textcoexact = deltapsi Divergence-free, no potential Magnetic field, solenoidal flow\nh (harmonic) Both curl-free and divergence-free Topological obstruction, DC current on a ring\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Example:-sphere-(genus-0)","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Example: sphere (genus 0)","text":"For a gradient 1-form alpha = d_0 u (exact by construction):\n\nalpha_textexact approx alpha\nalpha_textcoexact approx 0\nh approx 0\n\nu = [p[3] for p in mesh.points]   # height function z\nα = dec.d0 * u                    # exact 1-form\n\nresult = hodge_decompose_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α)\nprintln(norm(result.coexact))    # → ~1e-12\nprintln(norm(result.harmonic))   # → ~1e-12\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Example:-torus-(genus-1)","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Example: torus (genus 1)","text":"On the torus there exist two linearly independent harmonic 1-forms dual to the two fundamental cycles (meridional circle and longitudinal circle).\n\nFor a non-exact 1-form on the torus:\n\n# Build a 1-form that winds around the torus once (not exact)\nα = build_winding_oneform(mesh)   # custom test form\n\nresult = hodge_decompose_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α)\nprintln(norm(result.harmonic))   # → significant — the harmonic component\n                                   # captures the topological winding\n\nThe harmonic part has the same L^2 norm independent of the particular representative chosen in the cohomology class.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#Potential-recovery","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Potential recovery","text":"The scalar potential phi satisfies:\n\nnabla_Gamma phi = alpha_textexact\n\nand the stream potential psi satisfies:\n\nmathrmrot_Gamma psi approx alpha_textcoexact\n\nThese potentials can be used to integrate trajectories, compute stream lines, or reconstruct the original 1-form:\n\nφ = result.phi   # scalar potential (vertex field)\nψ = result.psi   # stream function (vertex field)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#References","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"References","text":"Desbrun, M., Kanso, E., & Tong, Y. (2008). Discrete differential forms for computational modeling. In Discrete Differential Geometry, pp. 287–324.\nGu, X., & Yau, S.T. (2003). Global conformal surface parameterization. Proc. Eurographics Symposium on Geometry Processing.\nHirani, A.N. (2003). Discrete exterior calculus. Ph.D. thesis, Caltech.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"12_hodge_decomposition/#See-also","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"See also","text":"Discrete exterior calculus\nTangential vector calculus","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#Tutorial-4:-Reaction–Diffusion-(Fisher–KPP)","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Tutorial 4: Reaction–Diffusion (Fisher–KPP)","text":"This tutorial solves the Fisher–KPP equation on the sphere:\n\nfracpartial upartial t = mu Delta_Gamma u + alpha u(1 - u)\n\nThe Fisher–KPP equation models logistic population growth with diffusive spread. Starting from a localized initial condition, the solution evolves into a travelling wave that invades the sphere.","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#Mathematical-background","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Mathematical background","text":"Equilibria: u^* = 0 (unstable) and u^* = 1 (stable attractor).\n\nTravelling wave speed (on flat mathbbR^2): c^* = 2sqrtmu alpha\n\nOn a sphere the behaviour is more complex because the curvature modulates the wave and the geometry is bounded.","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#Setup","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Setup","text":"using FrontIntrinsicOps\n\nR    = 1.0\nmesh = generate_icosphere(R, 4)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)\n\nμ   = 0.02       # diffusion coefficient\nα   = 2.0        # reaction rate (logistic)\ndt  = 1e-3       # time step\nT   = 5.0        # final time","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#Initial-condition","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Initial condition","text":"Start with a small patch near the north pole:\n\nu = zeros(length(mesh.points))\nfor (i, p) in enumerate(mesh.points)\n    if p[3] > 0.8    # northern cap\n        u[i] = 1.0\n    end\nend","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#Integration-with-the-cache","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Integration with the cache","text":"cache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=μ, dt=dt, θ=1.0)\nR_fkpp = fisher_kpp_reaction(α)\n\nN_steps = round(Int, T / dt)\nt = 0.0\nfor n in 1:N_steps\n    step_diffusion_cached!(u, cache, R_fkpp, t)\n    t += dt\nend\n\nprintln(\"Final coverage: u > 0.5 at \", count(u .> 0.5), \" / \", length(u), \" vertices\")","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#Monitoring-the-solution","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Monitoring the solution","text":"To record the solution at intermediate times:\n\nu = zeros(length(mesh.points))\nfor (i, p) in enumerate(mesh.points)\n    u[i] = p[3] > 0.8 ? 1.0 : 0.0\nend\n\ncache    = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=μ, dt=dt, θ=1.0)\nR_fkpp   = fisher_kpp_reaction(α)\nsnapshots = [copy(u)]\ntimes     = [0.0]\n\nN_steps = round(Int, T / dt)\nfor n in 1:N_steps\n    step_diffusion_cached!(u, cache, R_fkpp, (n-1)*dt)\n    if n % 500 == 0\n        push!(snapshots, copy(u))\n        push!(times, n * dt)\n        println(\"t = \", times[end], \"  min=\", minimum(u), \"  max=\", maximum(u))\n    end\nend","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#Checking-the-maximum-principle","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Checking the maximum principle","text":"The Fisher–KPP equation has a maximum principle: if u^0 in 01, then u(t) in 01 for all t  0.  Check this numerically:\n\nprintln(\"u range: [\", minimum(u), \", \", maximum(u), \"]\")\n# Should remain within [0, 1] (approximately — IMEX can slightly exceed bounds)","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#Convergence-test-with-exact-solution","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Convergence test with exact solution","text":"For linear decay R(u) = -alpha u, there is an exact solution:\n\n# Decay test: exact solution = e^{-(μ λ₁ + α) t} z\n# λ₁ = 2/R² for ℓ=1 mode on unit sphere\nλ1 = 2.0 / R^2\nα_decay = 0.5\nR_decay = linear_decay_reaction(α_decay)\n\nu0 = [p[3] for p in mesh.points]   # ℓ=1 mode\nu  = copy(u0)\n\ncache_decay = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=μ, dt=dt, θ=1.0)\nT_final = 1.0\nN = round(Int, T_final / dt)\n\nfor n in 1:N\n    step_diffusion_cached!(u, cache_decay, R_decay, (n-1)*dt)\nend\n\ndecay_exact = exp(-(μ * λ1 + α_decay) * T_final)\nu_exact     = decay_exact .* u0\nerr         = maximum(abs, u .- u_exact)\nprintln(\"Linear decay error: $err   (expected ~$(dt * (μ*λ1 + α_decay)))\")","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#Custom-reaction-term","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Custom reaction term","text":"Define your own reaction term as a pointwise callback:\n\n# Bistable / Allen–Cahn reaction\nbistable(u, x, t) = 5.0 * u * (1 - u) * (u - 0.5)\n\nu = rand(length(mesh.points))   # random initial data in [0,1]\ncache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=0.01, dt=1e-3, θ=1.0)\n\nfor n in 1:2000\n    step_diffusion_cached!(u, cache, bistable, n*1e-3)\nend\n\n# Solution should approach a pattern of u ≈ 0 and u ≈ 1 domains\nprintln(\"u < 0.2:  \", count(u .< 0.2), \" vertices\")\nprintln(\"u > 0.8:  \", count(u .> 0.8), \" vertices\")","category":"section"},{"location":"04_reaction_diffusion/#See-also","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"See also","text":"Surface diffusion tutorial\nMath: Reaction–diffusion\nMath: Caching and performance\nAPI: PDE solvers","category":"section"},{"location":"09_advection_diffusion/#Advection–Diffusion-IMEX","page":"Advection-Diffusion","title":"Advection–Diffusion IMEX","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"09_advection_diffusion/#Overview","page":"Advection-Diffusion","title":"Overview","text":"The advection–diffusion equation on a surface combines transport by a prescribed velocity field with diffusive smoothing:\n\nfracpartial upartial t + nabla_Gamma cdot (v u) = mu Delta_Gamma u + g\n\nFrontIntrinsicOps.jl solves this with an IMEX splitting (IMplicit–EXplicit): transport is treated explicitly (cheap, easy to upwind) while diffusion is treated implicitly (unconditionally stable for any mu dt).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"09_advection_diffusion/#IMEX-splitting","page":"Advection-Diffusion","title":"IMEX splitting","text":"Let:\n\nA\n= transport operator (see Scalar transport)\nL\n= Laplace–Beltrami operator (see Laplace–Beltrami)\nM = star_0\n= mass matrix\n\nThe semi-discrete equation is:\n\nM fracdudt + A u = mu L_M u + M g quad L_M = M L\n\nWait — more precisely the strong form after dividing by M:\n\nfracdudt = -M^-1 A u - mu L u + g\n\nOne IMEX step (explicit transport, implicit diffusion):\n\n(M + dtmuL) u^n+1 = M u^n - dt A u^n + dt M g^n\n\nwhich can be rewritten as:\n\n(I + dtmuM^-1 L) u^n+1 = u^n - dt M^-1 A u^n + dt g^n\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"09_advection_diffusion/#Stability-analysis","page":"Advection-Diffusion","title":"Stability analysis","text":"For purely diffusive (A = 0) the implicit step is unconditionally stable.\n\nFor purely transport (mu = 0) the explicit step requires the CFL condition (see Transport).\n\nFor the combined system the transport CFL dominates:\n\ndt leq dt_textCFL = C_textCFL cdot min_i fracA_i^*sum_e ni i w_e v_e ell_e\n\nThe diffusion term is always stable for any dt once it is treated implicitly.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"09_advection_diffusion/#Factorization-reuse","page":"Advection-Diffusion","title":"Factorization reuse","text":"The matrix (M + dtmuL) depends only on the constant parameters dt and mu.  Pre-factorising it once and reusing across time steps gives a large speedup:\n\n# First step: assembles and factorises (expensive)\nu, fac = step_surface_advection_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, vel, dt, μ;\n                                                scheme=:upwind)\n\n# Subsequent steps: reuses factorisation (cheap)\nA = assemble_transport_operator(mesh, geom, vel; scheme=:upwind)\nfor _ in 2:N\n    u, _ = step_surface_advection_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, vel, dt, μ;\n                                                  scheme=:upwind,\n                                                  transport_operator = A,\n                                                  factorization      = fac)\nend\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"09_advection_diffusion/#Fully-implicit-(backward-Euler)-variant","page":"Advection-Diffusion","title":"Fully implicit (backward Euler) variant","text":"An alternative fully-implicit step treats both transport and diffusion implicitly:\n\n(M + dtA + dtmuL) u^n+1 = M u^n + dt M g^n\n\nThis is more expensive per step (larger solve) and the transport operator A may not be symmetric.  Use when the velocity is slow relative to diffusion.\n\nu = step_surface_advection_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u, vel, dt, μ)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"09_advection_diffusion/#Convergence-rates","page":"Advection-Diffusion","title":"Convergence rates","text":"On the unit sphere, transporting u_0 = z with v = (-y x 0) and mu = 001:\n\nTransport scheme Spatial rate\nUpwind O(h^1) — first-order numerical diffusion\nCentered O(h^2) — matches Laplace–Beltrami accuracy\n\nFor fixed coarse mesh and varying dt (backward Euler in time):\n\nMethod Time rate\nIMEX (transport explicit, diffusion implicit) O(dt^1)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"09_advection_diffusion/#Assembling-the-transport-operator-once","page":"Advection-Diffusion","title":"Assembling the transport operator once","text":"# Pre-assemble A (constant velocity)\nA = assemble_transport_operator(mesh, geom, vel; scheme=:upwind)\n\n# CFL time step\ndt = estimate_transport_dt(mesh, geom, vel; cfl=0.3)\n\n# Integrate\nu, fac = step_surface_advection_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, vel, dt, μ;\n                                                scheme=:upwind,\n                                                transport_operator=A)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"09_advection_diffusion/#See-also","page":"Advection-Diffusion","title":"See also","text":"Scalar transport\nSurface diffusion\nReaction–diffusion IMEX","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Tutorial-1:-Getting-Started","page":"Getting Started","title":"Tutorial 1: Getting Started","text":"This tutorial shows how to set up FrontIntrinsicOps.jl, generate a sphere mesh, and compute basic geometric quantities — all in less than 20 lines of code.","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Prerequisites","page":"Getting Started","title":"Prerequisites","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.add(\"FrontIntrinsicOps\")","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Step-1:-Generate-a-mesh","page":"Getting Started","title":"Step 1: Generate a mesh","text":"using FrontIntrinsicOps\n\nR    = 1.0\nmesh = generate_icosphere(R, 3)   # level-3 icosphere: 642 vertices, 1280 faces\n\nThe level-3 icosphere provides mesh size h approx 014.  Use level 4 or 5 for convergence studies.","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Step-2:-Compute-geometry","page":"Getting Started","title":"Step 2: Compute geometry","text":"geom = compute_geometry(mesh)   # barycentric dual areas (default)\n\nThis fills geom.face_normals, geom.face_areas, geom.edge_lengths, geom.vertex_dual_areas, and geom.vertex_normals.","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Step-3:-Build-DEC-operators","page":"Getting Started","title":"Step 3: Build DEC operators","text":"dec = build_dec(mesh, geom)\n\nThis assembles:\n\ndec.d0 — vertex-to-edge coboundary d_0\ndec.d1 — edge-to-face coboundary d_1\ndec.star0 — Hodge star star_0 (dual areas)\ndec.star1 — Hodge star star_1 (cotan weights)\ndec.laplacian — Laplace–Beltrami L = star_0^-1 d_0^top star_1 d_0","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Step-4:-Geometric-checks","page":"Getting Started","title":"Step 4: Geometric checks","text":"println(\"Area           = \", measure(mesh, geom))        # ≈ 4π ≈ 12.566\nprintln(\"Enclosed vol.  = \", enclosed_measure(mesh))     # ≈ (4/3)π ≈ 4.189\nprintln(\"Euler χ        = \", euler_characteristic(mesh)) # = 2 for sphere\nprintln(\"Gauss–Bonnet   = \", gauss_bonnet_residual(mesh, geom))  # ≈ 0\n\nFor a sphere of radius R = 1:\n\nQuantity Exact Numerical (level 3)\nSurface area 4pi approx 12566 1256\nEnclosed volume frac43pi approx 4189 417\nEuler char. 2 2 (exact)\nGauss–Bonnet residual 0  10^-12","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Step-5:-Curvature","page":"Getting Started","title":"Step 5: Curvature","text":"H = mean_curvature(mesh, geom, dec)\nK = gaussian_curvature(mesh, geom)\n\nprintln(\"Mean curvature: min=\", minimum(H), \"  max=\", maximum(H))\n# ≈ [1.0, 1.0] for sphere of radius 1\n\nprintln(\"Gaussian curvature: min=\", minimum(K), \"  max=\", maximum(K))\n# ≈ [1.0, 1.0] for sphere of radius 1\n\nprintln(\"∫K dA = \", integrated_gaussian_curvature(mesh, geom))\n# ≈ 4π ≈ 12.566","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Step-6:-DEC-diagnostics","page":"Getting Started","title":"Step 6: DEC diagnostics","text":"report = check_dec(mesh, geom, dec; tol=1e-10)\nprintln(report.d1_d0_zero)          # true: d₁ d₀ = 0\nprintln(report.lap_constant_nullspace) # true: L 1 ≈ 0\nprintln(report.star0_positive)      # true: all dual areas > 0","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Step-7:-Apply-the-Laplacian","page":"Getting Started","title":"Step 7: Apply the Laplacian","text":"For a smooth function u = z on the sphere, -Delta_Gamma z = (2R^2) z:\n\nu  = [p[3] for p in mesh.points]   # z-coordinate at each vertex\nLu = dec.laplacian * u             # L u ≈ (2/R²) u\n\nerr = maximum(abs, Lu .- 2.0 .* u)\nprintln(\"Eigenvalue error: $err\")   # → ~1e-2 at level 3, → 0 as level → ∞","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Complete-script","page":"Getting Started","title":"Complete script","text":"using FrontIntrinsicOps\n\nR    = 1.0\nmesh = generate_icosphere(R, 3)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)\n\nprintln(\"=== Geometric quantities ===\")\nprintln(\"Area       = \", measure(mesh, geom))\nprintln(\"Volume     = \", enclosed_measure(mesh))\nprintln(\"χ          = \", euler_characteristic(mesh))\nprintln(\"GB residual = \", gauss_bonnet_residual(mesh, geom))\n\nH = mean_curvature(mesh, geom, dec)\nprintln(\"\\n=== Curvature ===\")\nprintln(\"H range = [\", minimum(H), \", \", maximum(H), \"]   (exact: 1.0)\")\n\nprintln(\"\\n=== DEC check ===\")\nrpt = check_dec(mesh, geom, dec)\nprintln(\"d1∘d0 = 0 : \", rpt.d1_d0_zero)\nprintln(\"L nullspace: \", rpt.lap_constant_nullspace)","category":"section"},{"location":"01_getting_started/#Next-steps","page":"Getting Started","title":"Next steps","text":"Surface diffusion tutorial\nScalar transport tutorial\nMath: Discrete geometry\nAPI: Geometry and DEC","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#Mesh-Types-and-Data-Structures","page":"Mesh Types","title":"Mesh Types and Data Structures","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#Overview","page":"Mesh Types","title":"Overview","text":"FrontIntrinsicOps.jl represents meshes as plain Julia structs containing arrays of vertices, edges, and faces.  The package is parameterised on the floating-point precision T (default Float64).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#CurveMesh{T}","page":"Mesh Types","title":"CurveMesh{T}","text":"A closed or open 2-D polygonal curve in mathbbR^2 (or optionally mathbbR^3).\n\nCurveMesh{T}\n  points  :: Vector{SVector{2,T}}   # vertex coordinates\n  edges   :: Vector{Tuple{Int,Int}} # ordered edge list (i → j)\n  closed  :: Bool                   # true if last edge reconnects to vertex 1","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#Topology","page":"Mesh Types","title":"Topology","text":"An N-vertex closed curve has exactly N edges.  Edge k connects vertex k to vertex k+1 (mod N).  An open curve with N vertices has N-1 edges.","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#Orientation-convention","page":"Mesh Types","title":"Orientation convention","text":"Edges are stored in traversal order.  The tangent field points in the positive traversal direction.  Vertex normals point 90° left of the tangent (i.e. inward for a counterclockwise curve).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#SurfaceMesh{T}","page":"Mesh Types","title":"SurfaceMesh{T}","text":"A triangulated closed or open surface in mathbbR^3.\n\nSurfaceMesh{T}\n  points :: Vector{SVector{3,T}}       # N_V vertex positions\n  faces  :: Vector{Tuple{Int,Int,Int}} # N_F triangles  (a, b, c) 1-based\n\nEdges are not stored explicitly; they are derived on demand by build_topology and cached in MeshTopology.","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#Orientation-convention-2","page":"Mesh Types","title":"Orientation convention","text":"Every face triple (a b c) is assumed to be consistently oriented so that the outward normal is\n\nhatn_f = frac(p_b - p_a) times (p_c - p_a)(p_b - p_a) times (p_c - p_a)\n\nOn a closed, orientable manifold two adjacent faces must traverse their shared edge in opposite directions.  The function has_consistent_orientation verifies this property.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#CurveGeometry{T}-and-SurfaceGeometry{T}","page":"Mesh Types","title":"CurveGeometry{T} and SurfaceGeometry{T}","text":"These structs hold pre-computed intrinsic geometric quantities.  They are populated by compute_geometry(mesh) and should be treated as read-only after construction.","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#CurveGeometry{T}","page":"Mesh Types","title":"CurveGeometry{T}","text":"Field Type Description\nedge_lengths Vector{T} ell_e = p_j - p_i\nedge_tangents Vector{SVector{2,T}} Unit tangent (p_j - p_i)ell_e\nvertex_dual_lengths Vector{T} ell_i^* = (ell_e_i-1 + ell_e_i)2\nvertex_normals Vector{SVector{2,T}} Left-normal of averaged tangent\nsigned_curvature Vector{T} kappa_i (see Curvature)","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#SurfaceGeometry{T}","page":"Mesh Types","title":"SurfaceGeometry{T}","text":"Field Type Description\nface_normals Vector{SVector{3,T}} Outward unit normals hatn_f\nface_areas Vector{T} A_f = tfrac12 (p_b-p_a)times(p_c-p_a)\nedge_lengths Vector{T} Primal edge lengths ell_e\nvertex_dual_areas Vector{T} A_i^* (barycentric or mixed)\nvertex_normals Vector{SVector{3,T}} Area-weighted vertex normals\nmean_curvature Vector{T} H_i (filled by compute_curvature!)\ngaussian_curvature Vector{T} K_i (filled by compute_curvature!)\ndual_area_method Symbol :barycentric or :mixed\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#CurveDEC{T}-and-SurfaceDEC{T}","page":"Mesh Types","title":"CurveDEC{T} and SurfaceDEC{T}","text":"These structs bundle the discrete exterior calculus operators assembled from the mesh and its geometry.  They are populated by build_dec(mesh, geom).","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#SurfaceDEC{T}","page":"Mesh Types","title":"SurfaceDEC{T}","text":"Field Type Mathematical object\nd0 SparseMatrixCSC d_0  Omega^0 to Omega^1 (vertex-to-edge coboundary)\nd1 SparseMatrixCSC d_1  Omega^1 to Omega^2 (edge-to-face coboundary)\nstar0 SparseMatrixCSC star_0  Omega^0 to Omega^0 (diagonal, dual areas)\nstar1 SparseMatrixCSC star_1  Omega^1 to Omega^1 (diagonal, cotan weights)\nstar2 SparseMatrixCSC star_2  Omega^2 to Omega^2 (diagonal, face areas)\nlaplacian SparseMatrixCSC L = star_0^-1 d_0^top star_1 d_0\n\nSee Discrete Exterior Calculus and Laplace–Beltrami for the mathematics.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#Primal–dual-picture","page":"Mesh Types","title":"Primal–dual picture","text":"The DEC framework rests on a primal–dual mesh pair:\n\nPrimal mesh                Dual mesh\n──────────────────────     ─────────────────────────────\n0-cells : vertices         2-cells : dual faces (Voronoi)\n1-cells : edges            1-cells : dual edges\n2-cells : faces            0-cells : circumcentres\n\nIn practice FrontIntrinsicOps.jl uses a lumped / diagonal approximation of the dual:\n\nDual areas A_i^* approximate the Voronoi cell area at vertex i.\nThe off-diagonal geometry of the dual is absorbed into the cotan weights w_e = tfrac12(cotalpha_e + cotbeta_e) of the primal edges.\n\nThis choice keeps all global operators sparse and diagonal-dominant, which simplifies both assembly and linear solves.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#Memory-layout-and-indexing","page":"Mesh Types","title":"Memory layout and indexing","text":"Vertices are indexed 1 ldots N_V (Julia 1-based).\nEdges are canonically stored with the smaller index first: (i j), i  j. This guarantees uniqueness and makes edge lookup via a Dict or sorted list straightforward.\nFaces store the original orientation given at construction.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"01_mesh_types/#See-also","page":"Mesh Types","title":"See also","text":"Topology and incidence matrices\nDiscrete geometry and dual areas\nDiscrete exterior calculus","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#Mesh-Generators","page":"Generators","title":"Mesh Generators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#Overview","page":"Generators","title":"Overview","text":"FrontIntrinsicOps.jl provides analytical mesh generators for standard geometries.  All generators produce consistently-oriented, outward-normal meshes suitable for convergence studies.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#sample_circle-—-regular-polygon","page":"Generators","title":"sample_circle — regular polygon","text":"mesh = sample_circle(R, N)\n\nGenerates a regular N-gon inscribed in a circle of radius R in the xy-plane.\n\nVertices:\n\np_k = left(R cosfrac2pi kN R sinfrac2pi kNright) quad k = 0 ldots N-1\n\nConvergence:\n\nLength to 2pi R as N to infty with rate O(1N^2).\nEnclosed area to pi R^2 with rate O(1N^2).\nCurvature to 1R with rate O(1N^2).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#generate_uvsphere-—-UV-sphere","page":"Generators","title":"generate_uvsphere — UV sphere","text":"mesh = generate_uvsphere(R, nphi, ntheta)\n\nGenerates a latitude-longitude sphere of radius R with nphi meridians and ntheta latitude bands.\n\nParameterization:\n\np(phi theta) = left(Rcosphisintheta Rsinphisintheta Rcosthetaright)\n\nphi in 0 2pi)\n— longitude (azimuth), nphi values\ntheta in (0 pi)\n— colatitude (polar angle), ntheta values\n\nNotes:\n\nPole vertices are singular (high-valence, poor triangle quality).\nNot recommended for convergence studies — use generate_icosphere instead.\nUseful when longitude/latitude alignment is required.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#generate_icosphere-—-icosphere-(recommended)","page":"Generators","title":"generate_icosphere — icosphere (recommended)","text":"mesh = generate_icosphere(R, level)\n\nGenerates a sphere of radius R by recursively subdividing a regular icosahedron.\n\nAlgorithm:\n\nStart with a regular icosahedron (12 vertices, 20 faces).\nAt each subdivision level, replace each triangle by 4 sub-triangles (midpoint subdivision).\nProject all vertices to radius R.\n\nVertex counts by level:\n\nLevel N_V N_F\n0 12 20\n1 42 80\n2 162 320\n3 642 1280\n4 2562 5120\n5 10242 20480\n\nProperties:\n\nAll triangles have approximately equal area: ideal for convergence studies.\nNo singular vertices (uniform valence ≈ 6 for interior vertices).\nGaussian curvature convergence: O(h^2).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#generate_torus-—-standard-torus","page":"Generators","title":"generate_torus — standard torus","text":"mesh = generate_torus(R, r, ntheta, nphi)\n\nGenerates a torus with major radius R (distance from centre to tube centre) and minor radius r (tube radius).\n\nParameterization:\n\np(theta phi) = left((R + rcosphi)costheta\n                          (R + rcosphi)sintheta\n                          rsinphiright)\n\ntheta in 0 2pi)\n— toroidal angle (ntheta values)\nphi in 0 2pi)\n— poloidal angle (nphi values)\n\nTopology:\n\nGenus 1: chi = 0, int_Gamma K  dA = 0.\nTwo independent cycles: toroidal (theta) and poloidal (phi).\n\nConvergence reference: The torus is the canonical non-simply-connected closed surface for testing Hodge decomposition and transport convergence.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#generate_ellipsoid-—-axis-aligned-ellipsoid","page":"Generators","title":"generate_ellipsoid — axis-aligned ellipsoid","text":"mesh = generate_ellipsoid(a, b, c, nphi, ntheta)\n\nGenerates an ellipsoid with semi-axes a (along x), b (along y), c (along z).\n\nParameterization:\n\np(phi theta) = left(acosphisintheta bsinphisintheta ccosthetaright)\n\nWhen a = b = c = R: reduces to a UV sphere of radius R.\n\nCurvature formulas:\n\nMean curvature at the poles (0 0 pm c): H = (a^2 + b^2 - c^2)  (a^2 b c) (approximate; exact only for a sphere of revolution with a = b).\n\nUse in convergence studies: The ellipsoid geometry breaks spherical symmetry while remaining smooth and simply-connected.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#generate_perturbed_sphere-—-\"bumpy-sphere\"","page":"Generators","title":"generate_perturbed_sphere — \"bumpy sphere\"","text":"mesh = generate_perturbed_sphere(R, ε, k, nphi, ntheta)\n\nGenerates a radially perturbed sphere with equation:\n\nr(phi theta) = Rbigl(1 + varepsilon cos(kphi)cos(ktheta)bigr)\n\nin spherical coordinates, giving vertices:\n\np(phi theta) = r(phi theta) cdot left(cosphisintheta sinphisintheta costhetaright)\n\nParameters:\n\nR\n— base radius\nvarepsilon\n— perturbation amplitude (typically 005 to 03)\nk\n— mode number (typically 2–4; odd k breaks anti-podal symmetry)\n\nWhen varepsilon = 0: reduces to a UV sphere.\n\nUse in convergence studies: The bumpy sphere retains spherical topology but is distinctly non-spherical, making it ideal for verifying that PDE solvers do not exploit sphere symmetry.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#Mesh-quality-diagnostics","page":"Generators","title":"Mesh quality diagnostics","text":"mesh = generate_icosphere(1.0, 3)\ninfo = check_mesh(mesh)\nprintln(info)\n# (n_vertices=642, n_edges=1920, n_faces=1280, closed=true,\n#  manifold=true, consistent_orientation=true, euler_characteristic=2)\n\nAll built-in generators produce closed, consistently-oriented manifold meshes with the correct Euler characteristic.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#Summary-table","page":"Generators","title":"Summary table","text":"Generator Surface chi Triangle quality Notes\nsample_circle Circle (1-D) — Uniform 2-D curve\ngenerate_uvsphere Sphere 2 Poor at poles Avoid for convergence\ngenerate_icosphere Sphere 2 Excellent Recommended\ngenerate_torus Torus 0 Good Genus-1 reference\ngenerate_ellipsoid Ellipsoid 2 Moderate Non-spherical geometry\ngenerate_perturbed_sphere Bumpy sphere 2 Moderate Non-symmetric test\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"16_generators/#See-also","page":"Generators","title":"See also","text":"Mesh types and data structures\nTopology and incidence matrices","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#API:-PDE-Solvers","page":"PDEs","title":"API: PDE Solvers","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Surface-diffusion,-Poisson,-Helmholtz","page":"PDEs","title":"Surface diffusion, Poisson, Helmholtz","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Poisson","page":"PDEs","title":"Poisson","text":"solve_surface_poisson(mesh, geom, dec, f;\n                       gauge = :zero_mean,   # :zero_mean or :pin\n                       reg   = 1e-10) → Vector{T}\n\nSolve L u = f on a closed surface.  Enforces zero-mean solution.","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Helmholtz","page":"PDEs","title":"Helmholtz","text":"solve_surface_helmholtz(mesh, geom, dec, f, α) → Vector{T}\n\nSolve (L + alpha M) u = f.  Requires alpha  0.","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Diffusion-—-backward-Euler","page":"PDEs","title":"Diffusion — backward Euler","text":"step_surface_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ;\n                                       rhs           = nothing,\n                                       factorization = nothing) → (u_new, fac)\n\nOne backward-Euler step: (M + dtmuL) u^n+1 = M u^n + dt g. Pass factorization=fac on subsequent steps to reuse the LU factorization.","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Diffusion-—-Crank–Nicolson","page":"PDEs","title":"Diffusion — Crank–Nicolson","text":"step_surface_diffusion_crank_nicolson(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ;\n                                       rhs           = nothing,\n                                       factorization = nothing) → (u_new, fac)\n\nSecond-order accurate.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Transport","page":"PDEs","title":"Transport","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Operator-assembly","page":"PDEs","title":"Operator assembly","text":"assemble_transport_operator(mesh, geom, vel;\n                              scheme = :upwind) → SparseMatrixCSC\n# scheme: :upwind (1st order) or :centered (2nd order)","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#CFL-estimate","page":"PDEs","title":"CFL estimate","text":"estimate_transport_dt(mesh, geom, vel; cfl=0.5) → T","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Time-steps","page":"PDEs","title":"Time steps","text":"step_surface_transport_forward_euler(mesh, geom, A, u, dt) → Vector{T}\nstep_surface_transport_ssprk2(mesh, geom, A, u, dt)       → Vector{T}\nstep_surface_transport_ssprk3(mesh, geom, A, u, dt)       → Vector{T}\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#High-resolution-transport-(v0.4)","page":"PDEs","title":"High-resolution transport (v0.4)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Limiters","page":"PDEs","title":"Limiters","text":"minmod(a, b) → T               # two-argument minmod\nminmod3(a, b, c) → T           # three-argument minmod\nvanleer_limiter(r) → T         # van Leer φ(r)\nsuperbee_limiter(r) → T        # superbee φ(r)","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Limited-operator-(solution-dependent)","page":"PDEs","title":"Limited operator (solution-dependent)","text":"assemble_transport_operator_limited(mesh, geom, topo, vel, u;\n                                    limiter = :minmod) → SparseMatrixCSC\n# limiter: :minmod, :van_leer, or :superbee","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Limited-transport-step","page":"PDEs","title":"Limited transport step","text":"step_surface_transport_limited(mesh, geom, dec, topo, u, vel, dt;\n                                limiter = :minmod,\n                                method  = :ssprk2) → Vector{T}\n# method: :ssprk2 or :euler\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Advection–diffusion-IMEX","page":"PDEs","title":"Advection–diffusion IMEX","text":"step_surface_advection_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, vel, dt, μ;\n                                       scheme             = :upwind,\n                                       transport_operator = nothing,  # pass to reuse\n                                       factorization      = nothing,  # pass to reuse\n                                       rhs                = nothing) → (u_new, fac)\n\nstep_surface_advection_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u, vel, dt, μ) → Vector{T}\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Reaction–diffusion-IMEX-(v0.4)","page":"PDEs","title":"Reaction–diffusion IMEX (v0.4)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Built-in-reactions","page":"PDEs","title":"Built-in reactions","text":"fisher_kpp_reaction(α) → Function       # f(u) = α u(1-u)\nlinear_decay_reaction(α) → Function     # f(u) = -α u\nbistable_reaction(α) → Function         # f(u) = α u(1-u)(u-0.5)","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Evaluate-reaction","page":"PDEs","title":"Evaluate reaction","text":"evaluate_reaction!(r, reaction, u, mesh, geom, t)\n\nDispatch to in-place, pointwise, or no-op reaction.","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#IMEX-step","page":"PDEs","title":"IMEX step","text":"step_surface_reaction_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ, reaction, t;\n                                      θ             = 1.0,\n                                      factorization = nothing) → (u_new, fac)\n\nstep_surface_reaction_diffusion_explicit(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ, reaction, t)\n  → Vector{T}   # unstable reference","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Full-integration","page":"PDEs","title":"Full integration","text":"solve_surface_reaction_diffusion(mesh, geom, dec, u0, T_end, dt, μ, reaction;\n                                  θ      = 1.0,\n                                  scheme = :imex) → (u_final, t_final)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Tangential-vector-calculus-(v0.4)","page":"PDEs","title":"Tangential vector calculus (v0.4)","text":"tangential_project(v, n) → SVector{3,T}\ntangential_project_field(mesh, geom, vfield; location=:vertex) → Vector{SVector{3,T}}\n\ngradient_0_to_tangent_vectors(mesh, geom, u; location=:face)  → Vector{SVector{3,T}}\ndivergence_tangent_vectors(mesh, geom, vfield; location=:face) → Vector{T}\n\ntangent_vectors_to_1form(mesh, geom, topo, vfield; location=:face) → Vector{T}\noneform_to_tangent_vectors(mesh, geom, topo, α; location=:face)   → Vector{SVector{3,T}}\n\nsurface_rot_0form(mesh, geom, u) → Vector{SVector{3,T}}  # n̂ × ∇Γu\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Hodge-decomposition-(v0.4)","page":"PDEs","title":"Hodge decomposition (v0.4)","text":"hodge_decompose_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α; reg=1e-10) → NamedTuple\n# Returns: (exact, coexact, harmonic, phi, psi)\n\nexact_component_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α; reg=1e-10)   → (α_exact, φ)\ncoexact_component_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α; reg=1e-10) → (α_coexact, ψ)\nharmonic_component_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α; reg=1e-10) → Vector{T}\n\nhodge_decomposition_residual(mesh, geom, dec, α, decomp) → T\nhodge_inner_products(mesh, geom, dec, decomp) → NamedTuple\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Open-surfaces-(v0.4)","page":"PDEs","title":"Open surfaces (v0.4)","text":"detect_boundary_edges(topo)          → Vector{Int}\ndetect_boundary_vertices(mesh, topo) → Vector{Int}\nis_open_surface(topo)                → Bool\n\napply_dirichlet!(u, bnd_verts, values)\napply_dirichlet_to_system!(A, b, bnd_verts, values)\napply_dirichlet_symmetric!(A, b, bnd_verts, values)\nadd_neumann_rhs!(b, mesh, geom, topo, g)\n\nboundary_mass_matrix(mesh, geom, topo) → SparseMatrixCSC\nsolve_open_surface_poisson(mesh, geom, dec, topo, f, bnd_verts, bnd_vals) → Vector{T}\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Cache-(v0.4)","page":"PDEs","title":"Cache (v0.4)","text":"build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec;\n                μ             = nothing,\n                dt            = nothing,\n                θ             = 1.0,\n                α_helmholtz   = nothing) → SurfacePDECache\n\nupdate_pde_cache(cache, mesh, geom, dec; kwargs...) → SurfacePDECache\n\nstep_diffusion_cached(cache, u)         → Vector{T}\nstep_diffusion_cached!(u, cache)        # in-place\nstep_diffusion_cached!(u, cache, R, t)  # with reaction\nsolve_helmholtz_cached(cache, f)        → Vector{T}\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Performance-(v0.4)","page":"PDEs","title":"Performance (v0.4)","text":"alloc_diffusion_buffers(nv, T=Float64) → SurfaceDiffusionBuffers\nalloc_rd_buffers(nv, T=Float64)        → SurfaceRDBuffers\n\nstep_diffusion_inplace!(u, cache, buf)\nstep_rd_inplace!(u, cache, buf, mesh, geom, R, t)\napply_mass_inplace!(y, cache, x)\napply_laplace_inplace!(y, cache, x)\n\nl2_norm_cached(cache, u)     → T    # √(u⊤ M u)\nenergy_norm_cached(cache, u) → T    # √(u⊤ L u)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#Shared-PDE-utilities","page":"PDEs","title":"Shared PDE utilities","text":"mass_matrix(mesh, geom)         → SparseMatrixCSC   # M = star0\nlumped_mass_vector(mesh, geom)  → Vector{T}\napply_mass!(y, mesh, geom, x)   # y ← M x\n\nweighted_mean(mesh, geom, u) → T\nzero_mean_projection!(u, mesh, geom)\nenforce_compatibility!(f, mesh, geom)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"pdes/#See-also","page":"PDEs","title":"See also","text":"Surface diffusion (math)\nScalar transport (math)\nReaction–diffusion (math)\nHodge decomposition (math)\nOpen surfaces (math)\nCaching (math)","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Caching-and-Performance","page":"Caching","title":"Caching and Performance","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Overview","page":"Caching","title":"Overview","text":"The cache and performance modules reduce the cost of repeated PDE solves by pre-assembling operators and pre-factorising linear systems.  The design goal is zero allocations per time step once the cache is built.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#The-bottleneck","page":"Caching","title":"The bottleneck","text":"Each implicit time step requires solving a linear system of size N_V times N_V. The typical workflow without caching:\n\nAssemble L (cheap, but non-trivial).\nForm (M + dtmuL) (cheap).\nFactorize the system (expensive, O(N_V^15) for sparse 2-D problems).\nSolve with the factorization (cheap, O(N_V) after factorization).\n\nWhen dt and mu are constant, steps 1–3 are identical at every time step. The cache layer builds these once and reuses them.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#SurfacePDECache","page":"Caching","title":"SurfacePDECache","text":"cache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec;\n                         μ         = 0.1,    # diffusion coefficient\n                         dt        = 1e-3,   # time step\n                         θ         = 1.0,    # implicit weight (1=BE, 0.5=CN)\n                         α_helmholtz = nothing)  # Helmholtz shift (if needed)\n\nThe cache stores:\n\ndec — the full DEC struct\nmass — the mass matrix M = star_0\nlaplacian — the Laplacian L\nsystem — the preassembled implicit matrix (M + dtthetamuL)\nfactorization — the sparse LU/Cholesky factorization of system\nμ, dt, θ — scalar parameters\n\nInvalidation: The cache must be rebuilt whenever dt, mu, or the mesh changes.  For time-varying problems with adaptive dt, call update_pde_cache.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Diffusion-step-(cached)","page":"Caching","title":"Diffusion step (cached)","text":"# Build once (expensive)\ncache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=0.1, dt=1e-3)\n\n# Step many times (cheap)\nfor _ in 1:1000\n    step_diffusion_cached!(u, cache)\nend\n\nInternally: u ← factorization \\ (M * u).  The factorization is reused.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Reaction–diffusion-step-(cached)","page":"Caching","title":"Reaction–diffusion step (cached)","text":"cache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=0.1, dt=1e-3, θ=1.0)\nR = fisher_kpp_reaction(2.0)\n\nfor n in 1:1000\n    step_diffusion_cached!(u, cache, R, n * cache.dt)\nend\n\nThe reaction vector R^n is evaluated and added to the RHS before each solve. The matrix factorization is reused.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Helmholtz-solve-(cached)","page":"Caching","title":"Helmholtz solve (cached)","text":"cache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; α_helmholtz=0.01)\nu = solve_helmholtz_cached(cache, f)\n\nUseful when many RHS vectors f must be solved with the same operator (L + alpha M).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Updating-the-cache","page":"Caching","title":"Updating the cache","text":"cache = update_pde_cache(cache, mesh, geom, dec; dt=5e-4)\n\nThis rebuilds the system matrix and refactorises.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#CurvePDECache","page":"Caching","title":"CurvePDECache","text":"The analogous cache for CurveMesh problems:\n\ncache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=0.05, dt=1e-2)\nstep_diffusion_cached!(u, cache)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Performance-buffers-(zero-allocation-kernels)","page":"Caching","title":"Performance buffers (zero-allocation kernels)","text":"For the tightest inner loops, the performance.jl module provides pre-allocated scratch buffers:\n\nbuf = alloc_diffusion_buffers(nv)   # SurfaceDiffusionBuffers\nbuf = alloc_rd_buffers(nv)          # SurfaceRDBuffers\n\nDiffusion step (in-place, no allocations):\n\nstep_diffusion_inplace!(u, cache, buf)\n\nReaction–diffusion step (in-place):\n\nstep_rd_inplace!(u, cache, buf, mesh, geom, R, t)\n\nIn-place matrix–vector products:\n\napply_mass_inplace!(y, cache, x)     # y ← M x\napply_laplace_inplace!(y, cache, x)  # y ← L x\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Norms","page":"Caching","title":"Norms","text":"l2 = l2_norm_cached(cache, u)       # ‖u‖_{L²} = √(u⊤ M u)\nen  = energy_norm_cached(cache, u)  # ‖∇u‖_{H¹} = √(u⊤ L u)\n\nThese reuse the cached mass and Laplacian matrices.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Memory-usage","page":"Caching","title":"Memory usage","text":"The dominant memory cost is the factorization, which for a sparse 2-D problem of size N_V requires O(N_V log N_V) memory (supernodal LU).  For a mesh with 10,000 vertices this is typically a few MB.\n\nLevel N_V approx Factorization size Step time\nIcosphere level 3 642 < 1 MB < 1 ms\nIcosphere level 4 2562 ~ 5 MB ~ 5 ms\nIcosphere level 5 10242 ~ 50 MB ~ 20 ms\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#Benchmark-pattern","page":"Caching","title":"Benchmark pattern","text":"using BenchmarkTools\n\nmesh = generate_icosphere(1.0, 4)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)\n\ncache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=0.1, dt=1e-3)\nbuf   = alloc_diffusion_buffers(length(mesh.points))\nu     = zeros(length(mesh.points))\n\n@benchmark step_diffusion_inplace!($u, $cache, $buf)\n# Target: 0 allocations, < 5 ms for level-4 icosphere\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"15_caching/#See-also","page":"Caching","title":"See also","text":"Surface diffusion\nReaction–diffusion","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Reaction–Diffusion-on-Surfaces","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Reaction–Diffusion on Surfaces","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Overview","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Overview","text":"The reaction–diffusion equation on a surface is:\n\nfracpartial upartial t = mu Delta_Gamma u + R(u x t)\n\nwhere mu  0 is the diffusion coefficient and R is the (generally nonlinear) reaction term.  This equation appears in:\n\nPattern formation (Turing instability, morphogenesis)\nPopulation dynamics (Fisher–KPP travelling waves on surfaces)\nChemical reactions on catalytic surfaces\nPhase-field models\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#IMEX-\\theta-scheme","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"IMEX theta-scheme","text":"The reaction term is treated explicitly (it is nonlinear and cheap to evaluate), while the stiff diffusion operator is treated implicitly.\n\nThe theta-scheme (where theta in 0 1 blends backward and forward Euler for the diffusion):\n\n(M + dtthetamuL) u^n+1 = (M - dt(1-theta)muL) u^n + dt M R^n\n\nwhere R^n_i = R(u^n_i x_i t^n) is evaluated pointwise.\n\ntheta Scheme Order Stability\n1 Backward Euler O(dt) L-stable\n05 Crank–Nicolson O(dt^2) A-stable (not L-stable)\n0 Forward Euler (unstable) O(dt) Conditionally stable only\n\nDefault: theta = 1 (backward Euler — recommended for stiff reactions).\n\nu, fac = step_surface_reaction_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ, reaction, t;\n                                               θ=1.0)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Reaction-API","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Reaction API","text":"Three forms are supported:","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#1.-Built-in-factory-functions","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"1. Built-in factory functions","text":"R = fisher_kpp_reaction(α)       # f(u) = α u(1-u)\nR = linear_decay_reaction(α)     # f(u) = -α u\nR = bistable_reaction(α)         # f(u) = α u(1-u)(u-0.5)\n\nEach returns a callable that is called as R(u_i, x_i, t).","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#2.-Pointwise-scalar-callback","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"2. Pointwise scalar callback","text":"my_reaction(u, x, t) = sin(x[1]) * u - u^3\nu, fac = step_surface_reaction_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ,\n                                               my_reaction, t)","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#3.-In-place-vector-callback","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"3. In-place vector callback","text":"For maximum performance (no allocations):\n\nfunction my_reaction!(r, u, mesh, geom, t)\n    for i in eachindex(u)\n        r[i] = 2.0 * u[i] * (1 - u[i])\n    end\nend\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Built-in-reaction-models","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Built-in reaction models","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Fisher–KPP-(logistic-growth)","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Fisher–KPP (logistic growth)","text":"R(u) = alpha u (1 - u)\n\nEquilibria: u = 0 (unstable), u = 1 (stable).\nTravelling wave speed: c^* = 2sqrtmu alpha.\nModels logistic population growth with diffusive spread.","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Linear-decay","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Linear decay","text":"R(u) = -alpha u quad alpha  0\n\nExact solution for decay from u_0: u(t) = e^-(lambda + alpha) t u_0 where lambda = mu lambda_ell is the diffusion eigenvalue.\nUseful for convergence testing (exact solutions known).","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Bistable-(Allen–Cahn-type)","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Bistable (Allen–Cahn type)","text":"R(u) = alpha u(1-u)(u - 05)\n\nThree equilibria: u = 0 (stable), u = 05 (unstable), u = 1 (stable).\nGenerates phase-field-like solutions with sharp interfaces.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Stability:-maximum-principle","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Stability: maximum principle","text":"For the Fisher–KPP equation with u^0 in 0 1, the continuous solution satisfies u in 0 1 for all t  0.  The IMEX scheme does not generally preserve this property exactly, but for small dt the solution remains close to 0 1.\n\nFor the Backward Euler (theta = 1) scheme with linear reactions, the discrete maximum principle holds if dt leq 1alpha.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Convergence-study","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Convergence study","text":"Test case: Linear decay on the sphere with exact solution.\n\nLet u_0 = Y_ell^m (spherical harmonic), R(u) = -alpha u:\n\nu(t) = e^-(mulambda_ell + alpha) t Y_ell^m\n\nwhere lambda_ell = ell(ell+1)R^2.  This yields an exact solution for convergence testing.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Time-integration-API","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Time integration API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Single-step-(IMEX)","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Single step (IMEX)","text":"u, fac = step_surface_reaction_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ, reaction, t;\n                                               θ=1.0)","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Full-integration","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Full integration","text":"u_final, t_final = solve_surface_reaction_diffusion(mesh, geom, dec, u0, T_end, dt,\n                                                     μ, reaction;\n                                                     θ=1.0, scheme=:imex)","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Explicit-Euler-(reference,-unstable-for-large-dt)","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Explicit Euler (reference, unstable for large dt)","text":"u_new = step_surface_reaction_diffusion_explicit(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ,\n                                                  reaction, t)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#Factorization-reuse","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"Factorization reuse","text":"For constant dt, mu, theta, the matrix (M + dtthetamuL) is the same at every step.  Passing back the factorization avoids recomputation:\n\nu, fac = step_surface_reaction_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ, R, 0.0)\nfor n in 1:N\n    global u, fac\n    u, _ = step_surface_reaction_diffusion_imex(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ, R,\n                                                  n*dt; factorization=fac)\nend\n\nOr use the cache layer which handles this automatically:\n\ncache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=0.1, dt=1e-3, θ=1.0)\nR = fisher_kpp_reaction(2.0)\nfor n in 1:N\n    step_diffusion_cached!(u, cache, R, n*dt)\nend\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"10_reaction_diffusion/#See-also","page":"Reaction-Diffusion","title":"See also","text":"Surface diffusion\nAdvection–diffusion IMEX\nCaching and performance","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Open-Surfaces-and-Boundary-Conditions","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Open Surfaces and Boundary Conditions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Overview","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Overview","text":"An open surface is a triangulated manifold-with-boundary.  The boundary partialGamma is a collection of edges each adjacent to only one face. This module provides:\n\nAutomatic detection of boundary edges and vertices.\nStrong Dirichlet boundary condition enforcement.\nSymmetric Dirichlet enforcement (preserves sparsity pattern).\nNeumann flux boundary condition assembly.\nA complete open-surface Poisson solver.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Boundary-detection","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Boundary detection","text":"A boundary edge is an edge with exactly one adjacent face:\n\nbnd_edges = detect_boundary_edges(topo)    # Vector{Int} — edge indices\n\nA boundary vertex is a vertex incident to at least one boundary edge:\n\nbnd_verts = detect_boundary_vertices(mesh, topo)   # Vector{Int} — vertex indices\n\nAn open surface has at least one boundary edge:\n\nis_open = is_open_surface(topo)   # Bool\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Dirichlet-boundary-conditions","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Dirichlet boundary conditions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Strong-enforcement-(asymmetric)","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Strong enforcement (asymmetric)","text":"For each boundary vertex v with prescribed value g_v:\n\nZero out row v in the system matrix A.\nSet Av v = 1.\nSet bv = g_v.\n\nThis enforces u_v = g_v exactly.  The resulting matrix is no longer symmetric.\n\napply_dirichlet_to_system!(A, b, bnd_verts, values)   # in-place modification","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Symmetric-enforcement","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Symmetric enforcement","text":"To preserve matrix symmetry:\n\nFor each Dirichlet DOF v with value g_v:\nZero out row v and column v.\nSet Avv = 1, bv = g_v.\nFor each interior neighbor j of v: subtract Ajv g_v from bj.\nThe resulting system has the same solution as the asymmetric form but preserves symmetry for efficiency.\n\napply_dirichlet_symmetric!(A, b, bnd_verts, values)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Neumann-boundary-conditions","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Neumann boundary conditions","text":"The Neumann condition prescribes the normal flux on the boundary:\n\nnabla_Gamma u cdot hatnu = g quad texton  partialGamma\n\nwhere hatnu is the outward boundary normal (in the tangent plane of Gamma, pointing away from the interior).\n\nThe weak form adds a boundary integral to the right-hand side:\n\nint_partialGamma g  phi_i  ds quad textfor each interior vertex  i\n\nDiscrete assembly:\n\nadd_neumann_rhs!(b, mesh, geom, topo, g)   # adds ∫_{∂Γ} g φ_i ds to b\n\nThe boundary mass matrix (1-D integral on partialGamma):\n\nM_b_ij = int_partialGamma phi_i phi_j  ds\n\nMb = boundary_mass_matrix(mesh, geom, topo)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Poisson-problem-on-an-open-surface","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Poisson problem on an open surface","text":"-Delta_Gamma u = f quad textin  Gamma setminus partialGamma\n\nu = g quad texton  partialGamma\n\nSolvability: With Dirichlet BCs on all of partialGamma, the system is uniquely solvable (no compatibility condition needed — the constant nullspace of L is broken by the boundary conditions).\n\nu = solve_open_surface_poisson(mesh, geom, dec, topo, f, bnd_verts, bnd_vals)\n\nAlgorithm:\n\nAssemble L (full Laplacian).\nApply apply_dirichlet_symmetric!(L, f, bnd_verts, bnd_vals).\nSolve the modified system.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Convergence-on-open-surfaces","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Convergence on open surfaces","text":"Test case (Laplace on a flat patch): Let Omega = 01^2 meshed as a flat triangulated square.  The exact solution u(xy) = x satisfies Delta u = 0.  For P1 finite elements the solution is exact (no discretization error).\n\nTest case (Poisson on a flat patch): The exact solution u(xy) = sin(pi x)sin(pi y) with f = 2pi^2 u satisfies Delta u = -f. Expected convergence rate: O(h^2) in the L^infty norm.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Detecting-open-vs.-closed-meshes","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Detecting open vs. closed meshes","text":"mesh_closed = generate_icosphere(1.0, 3)\nmesh_open   = generate_spherical_cap(1.0, 0.7, 30, 30)   # custom generator\n\ntopo_closed = build_topology(mesh_closed)\ntopo_open   = build_topology(mesh_open)\n\nis_open_surface(topo_closed)   # false\nis_open_surface(topo_open)     # true\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Boundary-normal-flux-evaluation","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Boundary normal flux evaluation","text":"After solving, verify the flux condition:\n\nflux = boundary_normal_flux(mesh, geom, topo, u)   # Vector{T} at boundary edges\n\nThe normal flux partial_nu u is approximated by a one-sided finite difference along each boundary edge.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#Relationship-to-Dirichlet-Laplacian","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Relationship to Dirichlet Laplacian","text":"On an open surface with Dirichlet BCs, the system matrix after BC enforcement has all real positive eigenvalues (it is positive definite).  The smallest eigenvalue corresponds to the first Dirichlet eigenfunction.\n\nFor the flat unit square the first Dirichlet eigenvalue is:\n\nlambda_1 = pi^2 + pi^2 = 2pi^2 approx 1974\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"14_open_surfaces/#See-also","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"See also","text":"Laplace–Beltrami operator\nSurface diffusion, Poisson, Helmholtz\nTopology and incidence matrices","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#API:-Diagnostics","page":"Diagnostics","title":"API: Diagnostics","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Mesh-checks","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Mesh checks","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#check_mesh","page":"Diagnostics","title":"check_mesh","text":"check_mesh(mesh::SurfaceMesh) → NamedTuple\n\nReturns a named tuple with:\n\nField Type Description\nn_vertices Int Number of vertices\nn_edges Int Number of (canonical) edges\nn_faces Int Number of triangles\nclosed Bool All edges have 2 adjacent faces\nmanifold Bool All edges have ≤ 2 adjacent faces\nconsistent_orientation Bool Interior edges traversed oppositely\neuler_characteristic Int chi = V - E + F\nwarnings Vector{String} List of detected problems","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#euler_characteristic","page":"Diagnostics","title":"euler_characteristic","text":"euler_characteristic(mesh) → Int    # V - E + F","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#is_closed-/-is_manifold-/-has_consistent_orientation","page":"Diagnostics","title":"is_closed / is_manifold / has_consistent_orientation","text":"is_closed(mesh) → Bool\nis_manifold(mesh) → Bool\nhas_consistent_orientation(mesh) → Bool\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#DEC-checks","page":"Diagnostics","title":"DEC checks","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#check_dec","page":"Diagnostics","title":"check_dec","text":"check_dec(mesh, geom, dec; tol=1e-10) → NamedTuple\n\nReturns:\n\nField Description\nd1_d0_zero Bool: d_1 d_0_infty  texttol\nd1_d0_max_residual T: \\max\nlap_constant_nullspace Bool: L mathbf1_infty  texttol\nstar0_positive Bool: all dual areas  0\nstar1_positive Bool: all cotan weights  0 (may be false for obtuse meshes)\nwarnings Vector{String}\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Gauss–Bonnet-diagnostic","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Gauss–Bonnet diagnostic","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#gauss_bonnet_residual","page":"Diagnostics","title":"gauss_bonnet_residual","text":"gauss_bonnet_residual(mesh, geom) → T\n\nReturns leftint_Gamma K  dA - 2pichiright.  Should be near machine precision for any mesh produced by the built-in generators.","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#integrated_gaussian_curvature","page":"Diagnostics","title":"integrated_gaussian_curvature","text":"integrated_gaussian_curvature(mesh, geom) → T    # Σ K_i A_i*\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Hodge-star-quality","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Hodge star quality","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#star1_sign_report","page":"Diagnostics","title":"star1_sign_report","text":"star1_sign_report(dec) → NamedTuple\n\nField Description\nn_entries Total number of ⋆₁ diagonal entries\nn_nonpositive Count of entries leq 0\nfrac_nonpositive Fraction of non-positive entries\nmin_entry Minimum value (negative if obtuse triangles present)\nall_positive Bool\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Laplacian-comparison","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Laplacian comparison","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#compare_laplace_methods","page":"Diagnostics","title":"compare_laplace_methods","text":"compare_laplace_methods(mesh, geom) → NamedTuple\n\nAssembles both L_textdec and L_textcotan and returns:\n\nField Description\nnorm_inf L_textdec - L_textcotan_infty\nnorm_frob L_textdec - L_textcotan_F\ndec_nullspace L_textdec mathbf1_infty\ncotan_nullspace L_textcotan mathbf1_infty\nmax_dec_res Maximum residual of DEC eigenvalue test\nmax_cotan_res Maximum residual of cotan eigenvalue test\n\nOn well-shaped meshes norm_inf < 1e-12.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#IO","page":"Diagnostics","title":"IO","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#Loading-meshes","page":"Diagnostics","title":"Loading meshes","text":"load_surface_stl(path::String) → SurfaceMesh{Float32}\n# Returns Float32 (native STL precision)\n\nload_curve_csv(path::String) → CurveMesh{Float64}\n# CSV format: one \"x,y\" or \"x,y,z\" coordinate per line\n\nload_curve_points(pts; closed=true) → CurveMesh{T}\n# pts: Vector{SVector{2,T}} or Vector{Tuple{T,T}}\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"diagnostics/#See-also","page":"Diagnostics","title":"See also","text":"Topology (math)\nGeometry (math)\nDEC (math)\nCurvature (math)","category":"section"},{"location":"03_transport/#Tutorial-3:-Scalar-Transport","page":"Transport","title":"Tutorial 3: Scalar Transport","text":"This tutorial transports a scalar field on the sphere by a rigid rotation velocity, using the SSP-RK3 time integrator with upwind and centered spatial schemes.","category":"section"},{"location":"03_transport/#Problem-setup","page":"Transport","title":"Problem setup","text":"Rigid rotation on the unit sphere:\n\nv(xyz) = (-y x 0)\n\nThis is tangential to the sphere and divergence-free (so the integral of u is conserved).\n\nInitial condition: u_0 = z (the height function).\n\nExact solution after time T: u(xyzT) = zcos T + sqrtx^2+y^2sin T (field rotated by angle T around the z-axis).","category":"section"},{"location":"03_transport/#Code","page":"Transport","title":"Code","text":"using FrontIntrinsicOps, StaticArrays\n\nR    = 1.0\nmesh = generate_icosphere(R, 4)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)\n\n# Velocity field: rigid rotation v = (-y, x, 0)\nvel = SVector{3,Float64}[SVector(-p[2], p[1], 0.0) for p in mesh.points]\n\n# Initial condition\nu  = Float64[p[3] for p in mesh.points]\nu0 = copy(u)\n\n# CFL time step\ndt = estimate_transport_dt(mesh, geom, vel; cfl=0.5)\nprintln(\"dt = $dt\")\n\n# Assemble transport operator (constant velocity)\nA_up  = assemble_transport_operator(mesh, geom, vel; scheme=:upwind)\nA_cen = assemble_transport_operator(mesh, geom, vel; scheme=:centered)","category":"section"},{"location":"03_transport/#Running-the-simulation","page":"Transport","title":"Running the simulation","text":"T_final = 0.5          # rotate by 0.5 radian\nN = round(Int, T_final / dt)\ndt = T_final / N       # adjust so we hit T_final exactly\n\n# Upwind + SSP-RK3\nu_up = copy(u)\nfor _ in 1:N\n    u_up = step_surface_transport_ssprk3(mesh, geom, A_up, u_up, dt)\nend\n\n# Centered + SSP-RK3\nu_cn = copy(u)\nfor _ in 1:N\n    u_cn = step_surface_transport_ssprk3(mesh, geom, A_cen, u_cn, dt)\nend","category":"section"},{"location":"03_transport/#Error-analysis","page":"Transport","title":"Error analysis","text":"# Exact solution: rotate u₀ by T_final around z-axis\n# For the field u₀ = z: exact solution is still z (z is rotation-invariant!)\nu_exact = Float64[p[3] for p in mesh.points]   # z is unchanged by z-rotation\n\nerr_up  = maximum(abs, u_up  .- u_exact)\nerr_cen = maximum(abs, u_cn  .- u_exact)\n\nprintln(\"Upwind error:   $err_up\")\nprintln(\"Centered error: $err_cen\")\n\nNote: Since u_0 = z is invariant under rotation around the z-axis, the exact solution is u(T) = z exactly.  Any error is purely numerical.","category":"section"},{"location":"03_transport/#Mass-conservation","page":"Transport","title":"Mass conservation","text":"mass0  = sum(geom.vertex_dual_areas .* u0)\nmass_up  = sum(geom.vertex_dual_areas .* u_up)\nmass_cen = sum(geom.vertex_dual_areas .* u_cn)\n\nprintln(\"Initial mass:         $mass0\")\nprintln(\"Upwind mass drift:    \", abs(mass_up  - mass0))\nprintln(\"Centered mass drift:  \", abs(mass_cen - mass0))\n# Both should be < 1e-12 (machine precision)","category":"section"},{"location":"03_transport/#Using-van-Leer-limiter-(v0.4)","page":"Transport","title":"Using van Leer limiter (v0.4)","text":"topo = build_topology(mesh)\nu_vl = copy(u)\n\nfor _ in 1:N\n    u_vl = step_surface_transport_limited(mesh, geom, dec, topo, u_vl, vel, dt;\n                                           limiter=:van_leer, method=:ssprk2)\nend\n\nerr_vl = maximum(abs, u_vl .- u_exact)\nprintln(\"Van Leer error: $err_vl\")","category":"section"},{"location":"03_transport/#Convergence-rate-study","page":"Transport","title":"Convergence rate study","text":"levels = [2, 3, 4, 5]\nerrors = Float64[]\n\nfor level in levels\n    m  = generate_icosphere(1.0, level)\n    g  = compute_geometry(m)\n    v  = SVector{3,Float64}[SVector(-p[2], p[1], 0.0) for p in m.points]\n    u0 = Float64[p[3] for p in m.points]\n\n    A  = assemble_transport_operator(m, g, v; scheme=:upwind)\n    dt_cfl = estimate_transport_dt(m, g, v; cfl=0.5)\n    N_steps = round(Int, T_final / dt_cfl)\n    dt_step = T_final / N_steps\n\n    u_k = copy(u0)\n    for _ in 1:N_steps\n        u_k = step_surface_transport_ssprk3(m, g, A, u_k, dt_step)\n    end\n\n    u_ex = Float64[p[3] for p in m.points]\n    push!(errors, maximum(abs, u_k .- u_ex))\nend\n\n# Print convergence table\nprintln(\"Level  N_V    L∞ error\")\nfor (i, level) in enumerate(levels)\n    nv = 12 * 4^level - 2 * 2^level + 2 # rough formula\n    println(\"$level      $nv    $(errors[i])\")\nend\n\nExpected convergence: upwind scheme achieves approximately O(h^1) in L^infty.","category":"section"},{"location":"03_transport/#See-also","page":"Transport","title":"See also","text":"Getting started\nMath: Scalar transport\nMath: High-resolution transport\nAPI: PDE solvers","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Laplace–Beltrami-Operator","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Laplace–Beltrami Operator","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Overview","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Overview","text":"The Laplace–Beltrami operator Delta_Gamma is the intrinsic Laplacian on a Riemannian manifold Gamma.  In local coordinates it generalises the flat Laplacian Delta = sum_i partial^2partial x_i^2 to curved surfaces.\n\nFrontIntrinsicOps.jl implements two numerically equivalent discretisations: the DEC factored form (default) and the direct cotan form.\n\nSign convention throughout this package:\n\nL = -Delta_Gamma quad text(positive semi-definite)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Smooth-definition","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Smooth definition","text":"On a smooth surface Gamma subset mathbbR^3 with metric g:\n\nDelta_Gamma u = frac1sqrtdet g sum_ij partial_i left(sqrtdet g g^ij partial_j uright)\n\nThe operator is self-adjoint with respect to the L^2(Gamma) inner product:\n\nint_Gamma (-Delta_Gamma u) v  dA = int_Gamma nabla_Gamma u cdot nabla_Gamma v  dA geq 0\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#DEC-factored-form-(method:dec,-default)","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"DEC factored form (method=:dec, default)","text":"L = star_0^-1 d_0^top star_1 d_0\n\nExpanded component-wise, the i-th row reads:\n\n(Lu)_i = frac1A_i^* sum_e ni i sigma_ei w_e (d_0 u)_e\n= frac1A_i^* sum_j in N(i) w_ij (u_i - u_j)\n\nwhere:\n\nN(i)\nis the set of vertices adjacent to i,\nw_ij = frac12(cotalpha_ij + cotbeta_ij)\nis the cotan weight for edge (ij),\nA_i^*\nis the dual area (from geom.vertex_dual_areas).\n\nMatrix form:\n\nL = underbracemathrmdiag(1A_i^*)_star_0^-1 underbraced_0^top star_1 d_0_textsymmetric\n\nThis factored form is numerically stable and directly reflects the DEC cochain structure.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Direct-cotan-form-(method:cotan)","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Direct cotan form (method=:cotan)","text":"Assembled by looping over triangles and distributing cotan contributions to edges:\n\n(L u)_i = frac1A_i^* sum_j in N(i) w_ij (u_i - u_j)\n\nThis is algebraically identical to the DEC form.  On well-shaped meshes L_textdec - L_textcotan_infty  10^-12.\n\nUsage:\n\nL_dec   = build_laplace_beltrami(mesh, geom; method=:dec)    # default\nL_cotan = build_laplace_beltrami(mesh, geom; method=:cotan)\n\nreport = compare_laplace_methods(mesh, geom)\nprintln(report.norm_inf)   # should be ~1e-14 on good meshes\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Properties-of-L","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Properties of L","text":"Property Statement\nSymmetry L^top = L\nPositive semi-definite u^top L u geq 0 for all u\nConstant nullspace L mathbf1 = 0; ker L = mathrmspanmathbf1 on connected closed surfaces\nRow-sum zero sum_j L_ij = 0 for all i\nSparse mathrmnnz(L) = N_V + 2 N_E (diagonal + off-diagonal pairs)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Spectrum-on-the-sphere","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Spectrum on the sphere","text":"On a sphere of radius R the exact eigenvalues of -Delta_Gamma are:\n\nlambda_ell = fracell(ell+1)R^2 quad ell = 0 1 2 ldots\n\nwith multiplicity 2ell+1.  In particular:\n\nell=0\n: lambda_0 = 0 (constant functions, nullspace of L).\nell=1\n: lambda_1 = 2R^2.  The eigenfunctions are x y z (coordinate functions).\n\nDiscrete verification:\n\nR    = 1.0\nmesh = generate_icosphere(R, 4)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)\n\nx = [p[1] for p in mesh.points]\nLx = dec.laplacian * x\nerr = maximum(abs, Lx .- (2/R^2) .* x)\nprintln(\"Eigenvalue error = $err\")   # → ~1e-3 at level 4, → 0 as level → ∞\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Poisson-equation","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Poisson equation","text":"L u = f quad textwith  int_Gamma f  dA = 0 text (compatibility)\n\nOn a closed surface L is singular (constant nullspace).  Two regularization strategies are implemented in solve_surface_poisson:\n\nTikhonov (gauge=:zero_mean): Solve (L + varepsilon I) u = f, then project u leftarrow u - bar u.  Default varepsilon = 10^-10.\nZero mean projection: enforce mathbf1^top star_0 u = 0.\n\nu = solve_surface_poisson(mesh, geom, dec, f; gauge=:zero_mean, reg=1e-10)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Helmholtz-equation","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Helmholtz equation","text":"(L + alpha M) u = f quad alpha  0\n\nwhere M = star_0 is the mass matrix.  For alpha  0 the system is non-singular even on closed surfaces.  The Helmholtz solve is the core building block for implicit diffusion and reaction–diffusion.\n\nu = solve_surface_helmholtz(mesh, geom, dec, f, α)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Backward-Euler-diffusion","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Backward-Euler diffusion","text":"fracdudt = -mu L u implies (I + dtmuL) u^n+1 = u^n\n\nu, fac = step_surface_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ)\n# Reuse factorization on subsequent steps:\nfor _ in 2:100\n    u, _ = step_surface_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ;\n                                                  factorization=fac)\nend\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#Crank–Nicolson-diffusion-(2nd-order)","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"Crank–Nicolson diffusion (2nd order)","text":"left(I + fracdtmu2 Lright) u^n+1 = left(I - fracdtmu2 Lright) u^n\n\nu, fac = step_surface_diffusion_crank_nicolson(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_laplace_beltrami/#See-also","page":"Laplace-Beltrami","title":"See also","text":"Discrete exterior calculus — derivation of L from DEC operators\nSurface diffusion, Poisson, Helmholtz — full solver details\nCurvature — mean curvature via L applied to coordinate functions","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#API:-Mesh-Generators","page":"Generators","title":"API: Mesh Generators","text":"All generators return a SurfaceMesh{Float64} (or CurveMesh{Float64}) with outward-oriented faces.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#Curves","page":"Generators","title":"Curves","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#sample_circle","page":"Generators","title":"sample_circle","text":"sample_circle(R::T, N::Int) → CurveMesh{T}\n\nGenerate a regular N-gon inscribed in a circle of radius R centered at the origin in the xy-plane.\n\nArgument Description\nR Circle radius\nN Number of vertices (= number of edges for a closed curve)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#1-D-point-front-helpers","page":"Generators","title":"1-D point-front helpers","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#single_marker_front","page":"Generators","title":"single_marker_front","text":"single_marker_front(xΓ; inside_right=true) -> PointFront1D\n\nCreate a one-marker front at xΓ.\n\ninside_right=true: inside is x >= xΓ\ninside_right=false: inside is x <= xΓ","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#interval_front","page":"Generators","title":"interval_front","text":"interval_front(xL, xR; interval_is_inside=true) -> PointFront1D\n\nCreate a two-marker front with strict ordering xL < xR.\n\ninterval_is_inside=true: inside is [xL, xR]\ninterval_is_inside=false: inside is exterior to [xL, xR]\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#Surfaces-—-sphere-variants","page":"Generators","title":"Surfaces — sphere variants","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#generate_uvsphere","page":"Generators","title":"generate_uvsphere","text":"generate_uvsphere(R, nphi, ntheta) → SurfaceMesh{T}\n\nUV (latitude-longitude) sphere of radius R. nphi meridional slices, ntheta latitudinal bands. Poor triangle quality at poles; prefer generate_icosphere for PDE studies.","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#generate_icosphere","page":"Generators","title":"generate_icosphere","text":"generate_icosphere(R, level::Int) → SurfaceMesh{T}\n\nIcosahedron recursively subdivided level times, then projected to radius R. Uniform triangle quality.  Recommended for all convergence studies.\n\nLevel N_V N_F Mesh size h (approx.)\n2 162 320 0.27\n3 642 1280 0.14\n4 2562 5120 0.07\n5 10242 20480 0.035\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#Surfaces-—-torus","page":"Generators","title":"Surfaces — torus","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#generate_torus","page":"Generators","title":"generate_torus","text":"generate_torus(R, r, ntheta::Int, nphi::Int) → SurfaceMesh{T}\n\nStandard torus with major radius R and minor radius r. ntheta toroidal samples, nphi poloidal samples. Topology: genus 1, chi = 0.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#Surfaces-—-deformed-geometries-(v0.4)","page":"Generators","title":"Surfaces — deformed geometries (v0.4)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#generate_ellipsoid","page":"Generators","title":"generate_ellipsoid","text":"generate_ellipsoid(a, b, c, nphi::Int, ntheta::Int) → SurfaceMesh{T}\n\nAxis-aligned ellipsoid with semi-axes a (x), b (y), c (z). UV parameterization with nphi × ntheta resolution. When a == b == c reduces to a UV sphere.","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#generate_perturbed_sphere","page":"Generators","title":"generate_perturbed_sphere","text":"generate_perturbed_sphere(R, ε, k, nphi::Int, ntheta::Int) → SurfaceMesh{T}\n\n\"Bumpy sphere\" with radial perturbation r(phitheta) = R(1 + varepsilon cos(kphi)cos(ktheta)).\n\nArgument Description\nR Base radius\nε Perturbation amplitude (0.05–0.3 recommended)\nk Perturbation mode (2–4 recommended)\nnphi Number of azimuthal samples\nntheta Number of polar samples\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"generators/#See-also","page":"Generators","title":"See also","text":"Mesh generators (math)\nTypes","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#API:-Geometry-and-DEC","page":"Geometry","title":"API: Geometry and DEC","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#Geometry","page":"Geometry","title":"Geometry","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#compute_geometry","page":"Geometry","title":"compute_geometry","text":"compute_geometry(mesh::CurveMesh) → CurveGeometry{T}\ncompute_geometry(mesh::SurfaceMesh; dual_area=:barycentric) → SurfaceGeometry{T}\n\nCompute all intrinsic geometric quantities.\n\nKeyword Values Description\ndual_area :barycentric (default) One-third of adjacent face areas\n :mixed or :voronoi Meyer et al. 2003 mixed Voronoi areas\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#DEC-assembly","page":"Geometry","title":"DEC assembly","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#build_dec","page":"Geometry","title":"build_dec","text":"build_dec(mesh::CurveMesh, geom::CurveGeometry) → CurveDEC{T}\nbuild_dec(mesh::SurfaceMesh, geom::SurfaceGeometry; laplace=:dec) → SurfaceDEC{T}\n\nAssemble the full discrete exterior calculus structure.\n\nKeyword Values Description\nlaplace :dec (default) L = star_0^-1 d_0^top star_1 d_0\n :cotan Direct cotan assembly (numerically equivalent)","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#build_laplace_beltrami","page":"Geometry","title":"build_laplace_beltrami","text":"build_laplace_beltrami(mesh, geom; method=:dec) → SparseMatrixCSC\n\nReturn only the Laplacian matrix (no other DEC operators).","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#laplace_beltrami","page":"Geometry","title":"laplace_beltrami","text":"laplace_beltrami(mesh, geom, dec, u::Vector) → Vector\n\nApply the Laplacian to a scalar field: returns L u.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#Hodge-stars-(individual-access)","page":"Geometry","title":"Hodge stars (individual access)","text":"hodge_star_0(mesh, geom) → SparseMatrixCSC   # diagonal: dual areas / lengths\nhodge_star_1(mesh, geom) → SparseMatrixCSC   # diagonal: cotan weights (surface)\nhodge_star_2(mesh, geom) → SparseMatrixCSC   # diagonal: 1/face_area\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#Exterior-derivatives-(individual-access)","page":"Geometry","title":"Exterior derivatives (individual access)","text":"incidence_0(mesh) → SparseMatrixCSC   # d0: N_E × N_V\nincidence_1(mesh) → SparseMatrixCSC   # d1: N_F × N_E\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#Codifferentials","page":"Geometry","title":"Codifferentials","text":"codifferential_1(mesh, geom, dec) → SparseMatrixCSC   # δ₁ = ⋆₀⁻¹ d₀ᵀ ⋆₁\ncodifferential_2(mesh, geom, dec) → SparseMatrixCSC   # δ₂ = ⋆₁⁻¹ d₁ᵀ ⋆₂\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#DEC-gradient-and-divergence","page":"Geometry","title":"DEC gradient and divergence","text":"gradient_0_to_1(mesh, dec, u)        → Vector  # d0 * u\ndivergence_1_to_0(mesh, geom, dec, α) → Vector  # δ₁ α\ncurl_like_1_to_2(mesh, dec, α)       → Vector  # d1 * α\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#Topology","page":"Geometry","title":"Topology","text":"build_topology(mesh::SurfaceMesh) → MeshTopology\n\nis_closed(mesh)                 → Bool\nis_manifold(mesh)               → Bool\nhas_consistent_orientation(mesh) → Bool\neuler_characteristic(mesh)      → Int    # V - E + F\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#Curvature","page":"Geometry","title":"Curvature","text":"# Curves\ncurvature(mesh::CurveMesh, geom) → Vector{T}         # signed κ\n\n# Surfaces\nmean_curvature(mesh, geom, dec) → Vector{T}           # scalar H\nmean_curvature_normal(mesh, geom, dec) → Vector{SVector{3,T}}\ngaussian_curvature(mesh, geom) → Vector{T}            # angle-defect K\ncompute_curvature(mesh, geom, dec) → SurfaceGeometry  # updates curvature fields\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#Integrals","page":"Geometry","title":"Integrals","text":"measure(mesh, geom) → T                          # total arc length or area\nenclosed_measure(mesh) → T                       # enclosed area or volume\nintegrate_vertex_field(mesh, geom, u) → T        # Σ u_i A_i*\nintegrate_face_field(mesh, geom, u) → T          # Σ u_f A_f\nintegrated_gaussian_curvature(mesh, geom) → T    # Σ K_i A_i*\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#Diagnostics","page":"Geometry","title":"Diagnostics","text":"check_mesh(mesh) → NamedTuple\n# Fields: n_vertices, n_edges, [n_faces], closed, manifold,\n#         consistent_orientation, euler_characteristic, warnings\n\ncheck_dec(mesh, geom, dec; tol=1e-10) → NamedTuple\n# Fields: d1_d0_zero, d1_d0_max_residual, lap_constant_nullspace,\n#         star0_positive, star1_positive, warnings\n\ngauss_bonnet_residual(mesh, geom) → T        # |∫K dA - 2πχ|\nstar1_sign_report(dec) → NamedTuple          # n_nonpositive, frac, min_entry\ncompare_laplace_methods(mesh, geom) → NamedTuple  # ‖L_dec − L_cotan‖\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"geometry/#See-also","page":"Geometry","title":"See also","text":"Geometry (math)\nDEC (math)\nLaplace–Beltrami (math)\nCurvature (math)","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#Topology-and-Incidence-Matrices","page":"Topology","title":"Topology and Incidence Matrices","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#Overview","page":"Topology","title":"Overview","text":"The topology module extracts all combinatorial structure from a SurfaceMesh (or CurveMesh) and assembles the incidence matrices that form the backbone of discrete exterior calculus.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#MeshTopology","page":"Topology","title":"MeshTopology","text":"build_topology(mesh::SurfaceMesh) → MeshTopology\n\nField Type Description\nedges Vector{Tuple{Int,Int}} All N_E canonical edges (ij)\nedge_index Dict{Tuple{Int,Int},Int} Fast lookup: edge → index\nface_edges Vector{Vector{Int}} For each face, the 3 edge indices\nface_edge_signs Vector{Vector{Int}} pm1 — does face traverse edge in canonical direction?\nvertex_faces Vector{Vector{Int}} For each vertex, adjacent face indices\nvertex_edges Vector{Vector{Int}} For each vertex, adjacent edge indices\nedge_faces Vector{Vector{Int}} For each edge, 1 or 2 adjacent face indices","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#Edge-canonicalization","page":"Topology","title":"Edge canonicalization","text":"Given a triangle with vertices (a b c), the three edges are represented as:\n\n(min(ab) max(ab))quad (min(bc) max(bc))quad (min(ac) max(ac))\n\nThis canonical form ensures each physical edge appears exactly once in the global edge list regardless of the faces it belongs to.","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#Boundary-detection","page":"Topology","title":"Boundary detection","text":"An edge is a boundary edge if length(edge_faces[e]) == 1.\n\nA mesh is closed if all edges are interior: is_closed(mesh).\n\nA mesh is manifold if all edges have at most 2 adjacent faces: is_manifold(mesh).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#Incidence-matrix-d_0-—-vertex-to-edge-coboundary","page":"Topology","title":"Incidence matrix d_0 — vertex-to-edge coboundary","text":"d_0\n\nis the exterior derivative on 0-cochains (scalar vertex fields). It maps a scalar u  V to mathbbR to a 1-cochain alpha  E to mathbbR:\n\nd_0 u_e = u_j - u_i quad e = (i to j)\n\nMatrix entry rule:\n\nd_0_ev = begincases\n+1  textif  v = j text (head of edge  e) \n-1  textif  v = i text (tail of edge  e) \n0   textotherwise\nendcases\n\nSize: N_E times N_V.  Each row has exactly two non-zeros: +1 and -1.\n\nPhysical meaning: (d_0 u)_e is the difference of u across edge e, i.e. the edge-based discrete 1-form representing the gradient of u.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#Incidence-matrix-d_1-—-edge-to-face-coboundary","page":"Topology","title":"Incidence matrix d_1 — edge-to-face coboundary","text":"d_1\n\nmaps a 1-cochain alpha  E to mathbbR to a 2-cochain beta  F to mathbbR:\n\nd_1 alpha_f = sum_e in partial f sigma_fe alpha_e\n\nwhere sigma_fe in +1 -1 is the relative orientation of edge e in face f with respect to the canonical edge orientation.\n\nMatrix entry rule:\n\nd_1_fe = begincases\n+1  textif edge  e text is traversed positively in face  f \n-1  textif edge  e text is traversed negatively in face  f \n0   textotherwise\nendcases\n\nSize: N_F times N_E.  Each row has exactly three non-zeros: +1, +1, -1 or -1, -1, +1 (depending on orientation).\n\nPhysical meaning: (d_1 alpha)_f is the circulation of alpha around the boundary of face f — the discrete analogue of the 2-form dalpha.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#The-chain-complex-identity:-d_1-\\circ-d_0-0","page":"Topology","title":"The chain complex identity: d_1 circ d_0 = 0","text":"This is the discrete analogue of d^2 = 0 (boundary of a boundary is empty).\n\nProof sketch: For any 0-cochain u,\n\nd_1 d_0 u_f = sum_e in partial f sigma_fe d_0 u_e\n= sum_e in partial f sigma_fe(u_j - u_i)\n\nEach vertex v in face f appears in exactly two edges of partial f, once as head and once as tail.  The orientation signs ensure these contributions cancel exactly: d_1 d_0 u_f = 0 for all f.\n\nNumerical check:\n\ndec = build_dec(mesh, geom)\nresidual = maximum(abs, dec.d1 * dec.d0)  # should be < 1e-14\n\ncheck_dec(mesh, geom, dec) reports this as d1_d0_max_residual.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#Orientation-consistency","page":"Topology","title":"Orientation consistency","text":"A mesh has consistent orientation if every interior edge (i j) is traversed as (i to j) by one adjacent face and as (j to i) by the other. In matrix terms this means the two non-zero entries in column e of d_1 have opposite signs.\n\nhas_consistent_orientation(mesh) checks this property.  STL files loaded by load_surface_stl do not guarantee consistent orientation; use a mesh repair tool if needed.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#Euler-characteristic","page":"Topology","title":"Euler characteristic","text":"For a triangulated 2-manifold (with or without boundary):\n\nchi = V - E + F\n\nSurface chi\nSphere 2\nDisk (open) 1\nTorus 0\nGenus-g closed surface 2 - 2g\n\nComputation:\n\nχ = euler_characteristic(mesh)   # returns V - E + F as Int\n\nThe Euler characteristic is topological: it is invariant under mesh refinement of the same underlying surface.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#Curve-topology","page":"Topology","title":"Curve topology","text":"For a CurveMesh, the topology is simply an ordered sequence of vertices. curve_vertex_order(mesh) returns the traversal order as a Vector{Int}.\n\nA closed curve has N edges and N vertices; an open curve has N-1 edges.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"02_topology/#See-also","page":"Topology","title":"See also","text":"Discrete exterior calculus — Hodge stars built on top of d_0, d_1\nOpen surfaces — Boundary edge/vertex detection","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#Discrete-Exterior-Calculus-(DEC)","page":"Discretization","title":"Discrete Exterior Calculus (DEC)","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#Overview","page":"Discretization","title":"Overview","text":"Discrete Exterior Calculus is a coordinate-free calculus on triangulated manifolds that mirrors smooth exterior calculus.  The key objects are:\n\nk-cochains — discrete k-forms: scalar values assigned to k-simplices (vertices, edges, faces).\nExterior derivatives d_0, d_1 — encode topological (combinatorial) differentiation.\nHodge stars star_0, star_1, star_2 — encode the metric (geometry) by mapping primal cochains to dual cochains.\n\nAll global operators are assembled as sparse matrices.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#The-cochain-complex","page":"Discretization","title":"The cochain complex","text":"Omega^0 xrightarrowd_0 Omega^1 xrightarrowd_1 Omega^2\n\nSpace Discrete object Size\nOmega^0 scalar vertex fields u  V to mathbbR N_V\nOmega^1 edge 1-forms alpha  E to mathbbR N_E\nOmega^2 face 2-forms beta  F to mathbbR N_F\n\nThe exterior derivatives d_0 and d_1 are the sparse incidence matrices described in Topology.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#Hodge-stars","page":"Discretization","title":"Hodge stars","text":"The Hodge star converts a primal k-cochain to a dual (n-k)-cochain (where n=2 for surfaces, n=1 for curves).  In the lumped / diagonal approximation used here, all three Hodge stars are diagonal matrices.","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#\\star_0-—-mass-matrix","page":"Discretization","title":"star_0 — mass matrix","text":"star_0 = mathrmdiag(A_1^* A_2^* ldots A_N_V^*)\n\nwhere A_i^* is the vertex dual area (barycentric or mixed — see Geometry).\n\nFor curves: star_0_ii = ell_i^* (vertex dual length).\n\nPhysical meaning: star_0 is the discrete mass matrix.  The integral of a vertex field is mathbf1^top star_0  u = sum_i A_i^* u_i.","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#\\star_1-—-edge-Hodge-star-(cotan-weights)","page":"Discretization","title":"star_1 — edge Hodge star (cotan weights)","text":"star_1_ee = w_e = frac12(cotalpha_e + cotbeta_e)\n\nwhere alpha_e and beta_e are the angles opposite edge e in the two triangles sharing it.\n\nFor a boundary edge (one adjacent triangle only): w_e = frac12cotalpha_e.\n\nFor curves: star_1_ee = ell_e  ell_e^*.\n\nPhysical meaning: star_1 encodes the dual edge length divided by the primal edge length.  On a Delaunay mesh this is the actual ratio of dual-to-primal edge lengths.  The formula w_e = frac12(cotalpha+cotbeta) is a classical result of Pinkall and Polthier (1993).","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#\\star_2-—-face-Hodge-star","page":"Discretization","title":"star_2 — face Hodge star","text":"star_2_ff = frac1A_f\n\n(inverse face area — maps primal 2-forms to dual 0-forms).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#Codifferential","page":"Discretization","title":"Codifferential","text":"The codifferential is the L^2-adjoint of the exterior derivative. In DEC it is:\n\ndelta_1 = star_0^-1 d_0^top star_1  Omega^1 to Omega^0\n\ndelta_2 = star_1^-1 d_1^top star_2  Omega^2 to Omega^1\n\nThese are assembled in kforms.jl.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#Hodge-Laplacians","page":"Discretization","title":"Hodge Laplacians","text":"The scalar Hodge Laplacian (Laplace–Beltrami on 0-forms):\n\nDelta_0 = delta_1 d_0 = star_0^-1 d_0^top star_1 d_0  Omega^0 to Omega^0\n\nThe sign convention in this package is L = -Delta_Gamma, so L is positive semi-definite (see Laplace–Beltrami).\n\nThe 1-form Hodge Laplacian:\n\nDelta_1 = delta_2 d_1 + d_0 delta_1  Omega^1 to Omega^1\n\nThis is the full Hodge Laplacian on 1-forms, used in Hodge Decomposition.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#DEC-gradient-and-divergence","page":"Discretization","title":"DEC gradient and divergence","text":"Gradient of a 0-form (vertex scalar):\n\nnabla_h u = d_0 u in Omega^1\n\nThis is a 1-form whose values are the differences u_j - u_i along each edge.\n\nDivergence of a 1-form:\n\nnabla_h cdot alpha = delta_1 alpha = star_0^-1 d_0^top star_1 alpha in Omega^0\n\nThese functions are accessible as gradient_0_to_1(mesh, dec, u) and divergence_1_to_0(mesh, geom, dec, α).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#Whitney-interpolation-and-the-geometric-meaning-of-\\star_1","page":"Discretization","title":"Whitney interpolation and the geometric meaning of star_1","text":"The cotan weight w_e arises naturally from the Whitney 1-form associated with edge e.  Given a scalar function u on a triangle with vertices a b c, the Whitney 1-form for edge (ab) is\n\nphi^ab = u_a lambda_b dlambda_a - u_b lambda_a dlambda_b\n\nwhere lambda_a lambda_b are barycentric coordinates.  Integrating the inner product langle phi^ab phi^ab rangle over the triangle yields the cotan weight.  This connection is made explicit in:\n\nDesbrun M., Hirani A.N., Leok M., Marsden J.E. (2005). Discrete exterior calculus.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#Key-identities","page":"Discretization","title":"Key identities","text":"Identity Meaning\nd_1 d_0 = 0 Boundary of boundary is empty\nstar_0 succ 0 Positive dual areas\nstar_2 succ 0 Positive face areas\nker(d_0) = 0 on trees Trivial for connected mesh\nker(d_1) supseteq mathrmim(d_0) Closed forms contain exact forms\n\\dim \\ker \\Delta_0 = $ 1 on closed surface Constant function\ndim ker Delta_1 = 2g on genus-g surface Harmonic 1-forms\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#Assemblying-the-DEC","page":"Discretization","title":"Assemblying the DEC","text":"mesh = generate_icosphere(1.0, 3)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)            # dual areas, edge lengths, etc.\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)             # d0, d1, star0, star1, star2, L\n\n# Access individual operators\nd0     = dec.d0      # N_E × N_V  sparse\nd1     = dec.d1      # N_F × N_E  sparse\nstar0  = dec.star0   # N_V × N_V  diagonal sparse\nstar1  = dec.star1   # N_E × N_E  diagonal sparse\nL      = dec.laplacian  # N_V × N_V  symmetric sparse positive semi-definite\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"04_dec/#See-also","page":"Discretization","title":"See also","text":"Topology and incidence matrices\nLaplace–Beltrami operator\nHodge Decomposition","category":"section"},{"location":"05_hodge_decomposition/#Tutorial-5:-Hodge-Decomposition","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Tutorial 5: Hodge Decomposition","text":"This tutorial demonstrates the Hodge–Helmholtz decomposition of a 1-form on the sphere (genus 0) and the torus (genus 1).","category":"section"},{"location":"05_hodge_decomposition/#Background","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Background","text":"Every 1-form alpha on a closed Riemannian manifold decomposes uniquely as:\n\nalpha = dphi + deltapsi + h\n\nExact part dphi: gradient of a scalar potential phi.\nCoexact part deltapsi: codifferential of a stream potential psi.\nHarmonic part h: topologically non-trivial, exists only on surfaces with genus g geq 1.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_hodge_decomposition/#Example-1:-Sphere-(genus-0,-no-harmonic-part)","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Example 1: Sphere (genus 0, no harmonic part)","text":"On a simply-connected surface all 1-forms decompose into exact and coexact components only; the harmonic part vanishes.\n\nusing FrontIntrinsicOps\n\nR    = 1.0\nmesh = generate_icosphere(R, 4)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)\n\n# Build an exact 1-form: α = d(z) = gradient of the height function\nu = [p[3] for p in mesh.points]   # z coordinate\nα = dec.d0 * u                     # α ∈ Ω¹ (exact by construction)\n\n# Hodge decomposition\nresult = hodge_decompose_1form(mesh, geom, dec, α)\n\nprintln(\"‖α_coexact‖ = \", norm(result.coexact))   # ≈ 0 (α is exact)\nprintln(\"‖α_harmonic‖ = \", norm(result.harmonic))  # ≈ 0 (sphere, genus 0)\nprintln(\"Residual = \", hodge_decomposition_residual(mesh, geom, dec, α, result))\n\n# Verify α_exact ≈ α\nerr = norm(result.exact .- α) / norm(α)\nprintln(\"Relative error ‖α_exact - α‖ / ‖α‖ = $err\")   # ≈ 0\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_hodge_decomposition/#Example-2:-Non-exact-1-form-on-the-sphere","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Example 2: Non-exact 1-form on the sphere","text":"Build a coexact 1-form: alpha = delta(z_f) (the codifferential of a face 2-form).\n\n# Build a face 2-form: ψ_f = area_f (or any face scalar field)\nz_face = [mean(mesh.points[v][3] for v in f) for f in mesh.faces]\nψ = z_face   # face 2-form\n\n# Compute codifferential: δ₂ ψ = ⋆₁⁻¹ d₁ᵀ ⋆₂ ψ\nstar1_inv = spdiagm(0 => 1.0 ./ diag(dec.star1))\nstar2     = dec.star2\ncoexact_alpha = star1_inv * dec.d1' * star2 * ψ\n\nresult2 = hodge_decompose_1form(mesh, geom, dec, coexact_alpha)\n\nprintln(\"‖α_exact‖   = \", norm(result2.exact))   # ≈ 0 (coexact form)\nprintln(\"‖α_coexact‖ = \", norm(result2.coexact))  # ≈ ‖coexact_alpha‖\nprintln(\"‖α_harmonic‖ = \", norm(result2.harmonic)) # ≈ 0\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_hodge_decomposition/#Example-3:-Torus-(genus-1,-non-trivial-harmonic-part)","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Example 3: Torus (genus 1, non-trivial harmonic part)","text":"The torus has genus 1 and first Betti number b_1 = 2.  There exist two linearly independent harmonic 1-forms dual to the toroidal and poloidal cycles.\n\n# Generate a torus\nmesh_t = generate_torus(3.0, 1.0, 60, 30)   # R=3, r=1\ngeom_t = compute_geometry(mesh_t)\ndec_t  = build_dec(mesh_t, geom_t)\n\nprintln(\"χ = \", euler_characteristic(mesh_t))   # = 0 (torus)","category":"section"},{"location":"05_hodge_decomposition/#Build-a-1-form-that-wraps-around-the-torus","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Build a 1-form that wraps around the torus","text":"The toroidal angle theta satisfies dtheta neq 0 globally but is not exact (not the differential of a global single-valued function).\n\n# Toroidal coordinate θ = atan(y, x): wraps around the torus once\nθ_vertex = [atan(p[2], p[1]) for p in mesh_t.points]\n# d(θ) as a 1-form (note: atan is multi-valued — treat it as approximate)\ndθ = dec_t.d0 * θ_vertex   # discontinuous across the branch cut\n\n# Decompose\nresult_t = hodge_decompose_1form(mesh_t, geom_t, dec_t, dθ)\n\nprintln(\"‖α_harmonic‖ = \", norm(result_t.harmonic))  # > 0 on the torus\nprintln(\"‖α_exact‖    = \", norm(result_t.exact))\nprintln(\"‖α_coexact‖  = \", norm(result_t.coexact))\n\nThe harmonic component captures the topological winding of dtheta around the torus.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_hodge_decomposition/#Orthogonality-check","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Orthogonality check","text":"The three components should be mutually orthogonal in the L^2 inner product langle alpha beta rangle_star_1 = alpha^top star_1 beta:\n\nips = hodge_inner_products(mesh, geom, dec, result)\nprintln(\"⟨exact, coexact⟩  = \", ips.exact_coexact)     # ≈ 0\nprintln(\"⟨exact, harmonic⟩ = \", ips.exact_harmonic)    # ≈ 0\nprintln(\"⟨coexact, harmonic⟩ = \", ips.coexact_harmonic) # ≈ 0\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_hodge_decomposition/#Recovering-the-potentials","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"Recovering the potentials","text":"The scalar potential phi solves Lphi = deltaalpha and the stream function psi solves tildeLpsi = dalpha:\n\nφ = result.phi    # scalar potential: ∇φ ≈ α_exact\nψ = result.psi    # stream potential: rot(ψ) ≈ α_coexact\n\n# The potential φ is defined up to a constant\nφ_normalized = φ .- sum(geom.vertex_dual_areas .* φ) / measure(mesh, geom)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"05_hodge_decomposition/#See-also","page":"Hodge Decomposition","title":"See also","text":"Math: Hodge decomposition\nMath: Discrete exterior calculus\nMath: Tangential vector calculus\nAPI: PDE solvers","category":"section"},{"location":"06_open_surfaces/#Tutorial-6:-Open-Surfaces-and-Dirichlet-Boundary-Conditions","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Tutorial 6: Open Surfaces and Dirichlet Boundary Conditions","text":"This tutorial solves the Poisson equation on an open surface (spherical cap) with Dirichlet boundary conditions.","category":"section"},{"location":"06_open_surfaces/#Problem-formulation","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Problem formulation","text":"Let Gamma_h be a flat square patch 01^2 triangulated uniformly. Solve:\n\n-Delta_Gamma u = f quad textin  Gamma_h\n\nu = g quad texton  partialGamma_h\n\nTest case 1: u(xy) = x (linear, f = 0).  The cotan Laplacian is exact for P1 functions so the error should be at machine precision.\n\nTest case 2: u(xy) = sin(pi x)sin(pi y) (manufactured solution, f = 2pi^2 sin(pi x)sin(pi y)).  Expected O(h^2) convergence in L^infty.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_open_surfaces/#Generating-an-open-surface","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Generating an open surface","text":"The built-in generators produce closed surfaces.  For this tutorial we construct a flat patch by hand:\n\nusing FrontIntrinsicOps, StaticArrays\n\nfunction make_square_patch(n)\n    # n×n grid of vertices, 2(n-1)² triangles\n    pts = SVector{3,Float64}[]\n    for j in 0:(n-1), i in 0:(n-1)\n        push!(pts, SVector(i/(n-1), j/(n-1), 0.0))\n    end\n    idx(i,j) = j*n + i + 1\n    faces = Tuple{Int,Int,Int}[]\n    for j in 0:(n-2), i in 0:(n-2)\n        a, b, c, d = idx(i,j), idx(i+1,j), idx(i+1,j+1), idx(i,j+1)\n        push!(faces, (a, b, c))\n        push!(faces, (a, c, d))\n    end\n    return SurfaceMesh(pts, faces)\nend\n\nmesh = make_square_patch(20)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)\ntopo = build_topology(mesh)\n\nprintln(\"Open surface: \", is_open_surface(topo))         # true\nprintln(\"Boundary verts: \", length(detect_boundary_vertices(mesh, topo)))\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_open_surfaces/#Test-case-1:-Linear-solution-u-x","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Test case 1: Linear solution u = x","text":"# Exact solution: u(x,y,z) = x\nu_exact = [p[1] for p in mesh.points]\n\n# Right-hand side: f = 0\nf = zeros(length(mesh.points))\n\n# Boundary values\nbnd_verts = detect_boundary_vertices(mesh, topo)\nbnd_vals  = [mesh.points[v][1] for v in bnd_verts]   # u = x on ∂Γ\n\n# Solve\nu = solve_open_surface_poisson(mesh, geom, dec, topo, f, bnd_verts, bnd_vals)\n\nerr = maximum(abs, u .- u_exact)\nprintln(\"Linear test error: $err\")   # ≈ machine precision (exact for P1)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_open_surfaces/#Test-case-2:-Manufactured-solution-u-\\sin(\\pi-x)\\sin(\\pi-y)","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Test case 2: Manufactured solution u = sin(pi x)sin(pi y)","text":"# Exact solution\nu_exact_mfr = [sin(π * p[1]) * sin(π * p[2]) for p in mesh.points]\n\n# Source term: -ΔΓ u = 2π² sin(πx)sin(πy)  (flat patch, Δ = ∂²/∂x² + ∂²/∂y²)\nf_mfr = [2π^2 * sin(π * p[1]) * sin(π * p[2]) for p in mesh.points]\n\n# Homogeneous Dirichlet BCs (u = 0 on ∂Γ since sin vanishes there)\nbnd_vals_zero = zeros(length(bnd_verts))\n\nu_mfr = solve_open_surface_poisson(mesh, geom, dec, topo, f_mfr,\n                                    bnd_verts, bnd_vals_zero)\n\nerr_mfr = maximum(abs, u_mfr .- u_exact_mfr)\nprintln(\"Manufactured solution error (n=20): $err_mfr\")  # ≈ 5e-3\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_open_surfaces/#Convergence-study","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Convergence study","text":"ns = [5, 10, 20, 40]\nerrs = Float64[]\n\nfor n in ns\n    m    = make_square_patch(n)\n    g    = compute_geometry(m)\n    d    = build_dec(m, g)\n    tp   = build_topology(m)\n\n    f_k  = [2π^2 * sin(π * p[1]) * sin(π * p[2]) for p in m.points]\n    bv   = detect_boundary_vertices(m, tp)\n    bval = zeros(length(bv))\n\n    u_k  = solve_open_surface_poisson(m, g, d, tp, f_k, bv, bval)\n    u_ex = [sin(π * p[1]) * sin(π * p[2]) for p in m.points]\n\n    push!(errs, maximum(abs, u_k .- u_ex))\nend\n\nprintln(\"n    L∞ error   rate\")\nfor i in 2:length(ns)\n    rate = log(errs[i-1]/errs[i]) / log(ns[i]/ns[i-1])\n    println(\"$(ns[i])    $(errs[i])   $(round(rate, digits=2))\")\nend\n# Expected: rate ≈ 2.0 (second-order convergence)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_open_surfaces/#Applying-Dirichlet-conditions-manually","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Applying Dirichlet conditions manually","text":"For full control over the system assembly:\n\nusing SparseArrays, LinearAlgebra\n\n# Assemble the raw Laplacian\nL = copy(dec.laplacian)\nf = [2π^2 * sin(π * p[1]) * sin(π * p[2]) for p in mesh.points]\nb = mass_matrix(mesh, geom) * f   # apply mass matrix to get RHS\n\n# Apply Dirichlet BCs (symmetric form — preserves sparsity pattern)\napply_dirichlet_symmetric!(L, b, bnd_verts, zeros(length(bnd_verts)))\n\n# Solve\nu = L \\ b\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_open_surfaces/#Open-surface-diffusion","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"Open surface diffusion","text":"Solving the heat equation on an open surface with fixed boundary:\n\nu = [sin(π * p[1]) * sin(π * p[2]) for p in mesh.points]   # initial condition\n\ndt = 0.001\nμ  = 0.01\n\nfor n in 1:100\n    # Assemble system with Dirichlet BCs\n    A = copy(dec.laplacian)\n    b = (mass_matrix(mesh, geom) ./ dt) * u\n    A_impl = mass_matrix(mesh, geom) / dt + μ * dec.laplacian\n    apply_dirichlet_symmetric!(A_impl, b, bnd_verts, zeros(length(bnd_verts)))\n    u = A_impl \\ b\nend\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_open_surfaces/#See-also","page":"Open Surfaces","title":"See also","text":"Math: Open surfaces\nMath: Surface diffusion\nAPI: PDE solvers","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#High-Resolution-Transport-with-Flux-Limiters","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"High-Resolution Transport with Flux Limiters","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#Overview","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"Overview","text":"The standard upwind scheme for scalar transport is only first-order accurate and introduces significant numerical diffusion.  High-resolution (HR) schemes combine upwind stability with near-second-order accuracy by using flux limiters that smoothly blend between first- and second-order approximations.\n\nFrontIntrinsicOps.jl implements the minmod, van Leer, and superbee limiters, together with an SSP-RK2 time integrator.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#Flux-limiter-theory","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"Flux limiter theory","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#The-limited-flux","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"The limited flux","text":"For edge e = (i j) with upstream vertex u and downstream vertex d:\n\nF_e = v_e left( u_textup + frac12 phi(r) (u_textdown - u_textup) right)\n\nwhere:\n\nu_textup\nis the value at the upwind vertex,\nphi(r)\nis the limiter function,\nr\nis the slope ratio:\n\nr = fracu_textup - u_textfar-upwindu_textdown - u_textup + varepsilon\n\nHere u_textfar-upwind is the second upwind neighbor (one step further upstream).\n\nWhen phi(r) = 0 the flux is pure upwind (first order). When phi(r) = 1 the flux is centered (second order, potentially oscillatory).\n\nTVD condition: A limiter is total variation diminishing if phi lies in the Sweby region:\n\n0 leq phi(r) leq min(2r 2) quad 0 leq phi(r) leq 2\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#Minmod-limiter","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"Minmod limiter","text":"phi_textmm(a b) = mathrmsign(a) cdot max(0 min(a  mathrmsign(a) b))\n\nEquivalently: if a and b have the same sign, return the smaller-magnitude value; otherwise return 0.\n\nphi_textmm(r) = max(0 min(1 r))\n\nMost diffusive of the three limiters.\nExactly one-sided near extrema.\nProvably TVD.\n\nφ = minmod(a, b)     # two-argument form\nφ = minmod3(a, b, c) # three-argument form: same-sign minimum\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#Van-Leer-limiter","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"Van Leer limiter","text":"phi_textvL(r) = fracr + r1 + r\n\nSmooth at all r (unlike minmod which has a kink at r=1).\nSecond-order at smooth extrema (unlike minmod which drops to first-order).\nTVD.\nRecommended for smooth solutions.\n\nφ = vanleer_limiter(r)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#Superbee-limiter","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"Superbee limiter","text":"phi_textsb(r) = max(0 min(2r 1) min(r 2))\n\nMost compressive of the three (closest to second-order everywhere).\nCan over-sharpen near genuine extrema.\nTVD but at the upper boundary of the Sweby region.\nRecommended when the solution is expected to have sharp but smooth fronts.\n\nφ = superbee_limiter(r)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#Assembling-the-limited-transport-operator","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"Assembling the limited transport operator","text":"A_limited = assemble_transport_operator_limited(mesh, geom, topo, vel, u;\n                                                 limiter=:minmod)    # :minmod, :van_leer, :superbee\n\nNote that unlike the standard upwind operator, the limited operator depends on the current solution u (through the slope ratio r).  It must be reassembled at each time step.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#SSP-RK2-time-integration","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"SSP-RK2 time integration","text":"The SSP-RK2 scheme is used for its strong-stability-preserving properties. Since the limited operator must be reassembled at each stage, two operator assemblies per step are required:\n\nStage 1:\n\nu^(1) = u^n - dt M^-1 A(u^n) u^n\n\nStage 2 (reassemble with u^(1)):\n\nu^n+1 = frac12 u^n + frac12 u^(1) - fracdt2 M^-1 A(u^(1)) u^(1)\n\nu_new = step_surface_transport_limited(mesh, geom, dec, topo, u, vel, dt;\n                                        limiter=:van_leer, method=:ssprk2)\n\nSet method=:euler for a single forward-Euler stage (cheaper but less accurate).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#Comparison-of-limiters","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"Comparison of limiters","text":"Limiter Accuracy Sharpness Recommended for\nNone (upwind) O(h) High diffusion Robustness only\nMinmod O(h^2) near smooth regions Moderate General use\nVan Leer O(h^2) smooth High Smooth solutions\nSuperbee O(h^2) aggressive Highest Sharp fronts\nNone (centered) O(h^2) Oscillatory Combined with diffusion only\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#CFL-condition","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"CFL condition","text":"The CFL condition for the limited scheme is the same as for the standard upwind scheme:\n\ndt leq C_textCFL cdot min_i fracA_i^*sum_e ni i w_e v_e ell_e\n\nFor SSP-RK2, the effective CFL coefficient can be taken up to 1.0; typical practice is C_textCFL = 05.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#Conservation","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"Conservation","text":"The limited scheme is locally conservative: the flux through each edge is antisymmetric (what leaves vertex i enters vertex j).  Global conservation:\n\nsum_i A_i^* u_i^n+1 = sum_i A_i^* u_i^n\n\nholds to machine precision for divergence-free velocity fields.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"13_highres_transport/#See-also","page":"High-Resolution Transport","title":"See also","text":"Scalar transport — standard upwind and centered schemes\nAdvection–diffusion IMEX","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#Tangential-Vector-Calculus","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"Tangential Vector Calculus","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#Overview","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"Overview","text":"This module provides a complete toolkit for intrinsic vector calculus on triangulated surfaces.  All operations work with the tangent bundle of the surface and are implemented using the DEC framework.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#Tangential-projection","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"Tangential projection","text":"For a vector v in mathbbR^3 and a unit surface normal hatn:\n\nv^tau = v - (v cdot hatn) hatn\n\nThis projects v onto the tangent plane.\n\n# Per vector\nv_tang = tangential_project(v, n)   # SVector{3,T}\n\n# Per vertex field\nv_tang_field = tangential_project_field(mesh, geom, vfield; location=:vertex)\n\nThe location keyword selects vertex-based (hatn_i) or face-based (hatn_f) normals for the projection.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#Surface-gradient","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"Surface gradient","text":"For a scalar vertex field u  V to mathbbR, the discrete surface gradient at each face f = (a b c) is computed from the Whitney 1-form formula:\n\nnabla_Gamma ubig_f = frac12A_f sum_v in f u_v left(hatn_f times (p_textopp(v) - p_v)right)\n\nwhere p_textopp(v) is the vertex of f opposite to v, i.e. the edge not containing v.  The result is a tangent vector in mathbbR^3 perpendicular to hatn_f.\n\nAlternative formula (equivalent, summing over edges):\n\nFor edge e_k = (v_i v_j) of face f, let p_k = p_i - p_j.  Then:\n\nnabla_Gamma ubig_f = frac12A_f sum_k u_k left(hatn_f times p_k^perpright)\n\nThis formula follows directly from differentiating the piecewise-linear interpolant over the face.\n\ngrad_u = gradient_0_to_tangent_vectors(mesh, geom, u; location=:face)\n# Returns Vector{SVector{3,T}}, one per face\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#Surface-divergence","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"Surface divergence","text":"For a tangential vector field w_f in T_fGamma (one vector per face), the discrete surface divergence is computed as:\n\n(nabla_Gamma cdot w)_f approx frac1A_f sum_e in partial f sigma_fe ell_e (w_f cdot hatt_e)\n\nAt vertices, the divergence is assembled by distributing face contributions using barycentric weights.\n\ndiv_w = divergence_tangent_vectors(mesh, geom, vfield; location=:face)\n# Returns Vector{T}, one per face\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#1-form-tangent-vector-conversion","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"1-form ↔ tangent vector conversion","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#Tangent-vectors-1-form","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"Tangent vectors → 1-form","text":"A tangential vector field w on faces is converted to a DEC edge 1-form alpha in Omega^1 by projecting w onto each edge tangent:\n\nalpha_e = w_f cdot hatt_e cdot ell_e\n\nwhere f is (one of) the face(s) adjacent to e.\n\nα = tangent_vectors_to_1form(mesh, geom, topo, vfield; location=:face)\n# Returns Vector{T}, length N_E","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#1-form-tangent-vectors","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"1-form → tangent vectors","text":"The inverse: reconstruct a tangential vector field from an edge 1-form.  For face f:\n\nw_f = frac12A_f sum_e in partial f sigma_fe alpha_e left(hatn_f times p_eright)\n\nwhere p_e = p_j - p_i is the edge vector.\n\nvfield = oneform_to_tangent_vectors(mesh, geom, topo, α; location=:face)\n# Returns Vector{SVector{3,T}}, one per face\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#Surface-rot-(tangential-curl)","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"Surface rot (tangential curl)","text":"For a scalar 0-form u, the surface rotation (or \"surface curl\" of a scalar) is:\n\nmathrmrot_Gamma u = hatn times nabla_Gamma u\n\nThis produces a tangential vector field perpendicular to nabla_Gamma u. On a simply-connected surface mathrmrot_Gamma u is divergence-free.\n\nrot_u = surface_rot_0form(mesh, geom, u)   # Vector{SVector{3,T}}\n\nApplication: Given a stream function psi, the velocity field v = mathrmrot_Gamma psi is automatically tangential and divergence-free — useful for constructing test velocity fields.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#Mathematical-consistency","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"Mathematical consistency","text":"The vector calculus operations are consistent with the DEC operators in the following sense:\n\nGradient–1-form duality: tangent_vectors_to_1form(gradient_0_to_tangent_vectors(u)) should approximate d0 * u (the DEC gradient).\nDivergence–codifferential duality: divergence_1_to_0(d0 * u) = L * u (Laplacian from DEC).\nGreen's identity: int_Gamma nabla_Gamma u cdot nabla_Gamma v  dA = u^top L v (exact for piecewise-linear u, v).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#Orthogonality-check","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"Orthogonality check","text":"After computing a tangent-vector field w, verify tangency:\n\nfor i in eachindex(w)\n    @assert abs(dot(w[i], geom.vertex_normals[i])) < 1e-10\nend\n\nThe tangential_project_field function ensures this by construction.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"11_vector_calculus/#See-also","page":"Vector Calculus","title":"See also","text":"Discrete exterior calculus — DEC gradient and divergence\nHodge decomposition — uses 1-forms and codifferentials\nHigh-resolution transport — velocity fields as tangent vectors","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Discrete-Geometry-and-Dual-Areas","page":"Geometry","title":"Discrete Geometry and Dual Areas","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Overview","page":"Geometry","title":"Overview","text":"The geometry module computes intrinsic geometric quantities on the primal mesh.  The key outputs are face normals and areas, edge lengths, and — most importantly for the PDE layer — vertex dual areas A_i^* that represent the area element associated with each vertex.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Face-geometry","page":"Geometry","title":"Face geometry","text":"For a triangle with vertices p_a p_b p_c in mathbbR^3:\n\nOutward face normal (unit):\n\nhatn_f = frac(p_b - p_a) times (p_c - p_a)(p_b - p_a) times (p_c - p_a)\n\nFace area:\n\nA_f = frac12 (p_b - p_a) times (p_c - p_a)\n\nInterior angles:\n\ntheta_a = arccosleft(frac(p_b - p_a) cdot (p_c - p_a)p_b - p_a p_c - p_aright)\n\nand cyclically for theta_b, theta_c.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Edge-lengths","page":"Geometry","title":"Edge lengths","text":"For a canonical edge (i j):\n\nell_ij = p_j - p_i\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Vertex-normals","page":"Geometry","title":"Vertex normals","text":"The vertex normal at v is an area-weighted average of the adjacent face normals:\n\nhatn_v = fracdisplaystylesum_f ni v A_f  hatn_fleftdisplaystylesum_f ni v A_f  hatn_fright\n\nThis is the most common definition for smooth-surface rendering and curvature estimation.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Dual-areas","page":"Geometry","title":"Dual areas","text":"The dual area A_i^* at vertex i serves as the integration weight for vertex-based fields.  It approximates the area of the Voronoi cell dual to vertex i.\n\nTwo formulations are supported via compute_geometry(mesh; dual_area=:xxx).","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Barycentric-dual-(:barycentric,-default)","page":"Geometry","title":"Barycentric dual (:barycentric, default)","text":"The simplest choice: each face contributes one third of its area to each of its three vertices.\n\nA_i^textbary = frac13 sum_f ni i A_f\n\nProperties:\n\nAlways positive.\nSums to the total surface area: sum_i A_i^textbary = A_Gamma.\nSimple and robust even for low-quality meshes.\nNot geometrically meaningful for the dual Voronoi cell on irregular meshes.","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Mixed-/-Voronoi-dual-(:mixed-or-:voronoi)","page":"Geometry","title":"Mixed / Voronoi dual (:mixed or :voronoi)","text":"Based on Meyer, Desbrun, Schröder, Barr (2003), this formula uses the actual Voronoi circumcentric areas for acute triangles and falls back to barycentric areas for obtuse triangles.\n\nFor each triangle T = (a b c) with opposite edge lengths ell_a ell_b ell_c and angles theta_a theta_b theta_c:\n\nCase 1: Non-obtuse triangle (all angles leq pi2):\n\nThe Voronoi contribution to vertex a is:\n\nA_a^textVor = frac18Bigl(ell_b^2 cottheta_c + ell_c^2 cottheta_bBigr)\n\nwhere ell_b = ac and ell_c = ab.\n\nCase 2: Obtuse at a (theta_a  pi2):\n\nA_a = fracA_T2 quad A_b = A_c = fracA_T4\n\nCase 3: Obtuse at b (or c): analogous with the obtuse vertex receiving A_T4 and the opposite vertex receiving A_T2.\n\nProperties:\n\nAlways positive (no negative areas).\nEquals the Voronoi cell area for Delaunay triangulations.\nMore accurate for curvature estimation than barycentric.\nSum: sum_i A_i^textmixed = A_Gamma.\n\nSelection:\n\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh; dual_area=:barycentric)  # default\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh; dual_area=:mixed)        # Meyer et al. 2003\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh; dual_area=:voronoi)      # alias for :mixed\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Curve-geometry","page":"Geometry","title":"Curve geometry","text":"For a CurveMesh the analogous quantities are:\n\nEdge length: ell_e = p_j - p_i\n\nEdge tangent: hatt_e = (p_j - p_i)ell_e\n\nVertex dual length:\n\nell_i^* = fracell_e_i-1 + ell_e_i2\n\nthe half-sum of the two adjacent edge lengths.\n\nVertex normal: The left-perpendicular of the averaged tangent at i.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Integration-formulas","page":"Geometry","title":"Integration formulas","text":"Given vertex-based field u and face-based field w:\n\nint_Gamma u  dA approx sum_i=1^N_V u_i  A_i^* qquad\nint_Gamma w  dA approx sum_f=1^N_F w_f  A_f\n\nTotal surface area and enclosed volume:\n\narea   = measure(mesh, geom)          # Σ A_f\nvolume = enclosed_measure(mesh)       # divergence theorem: (1/6)|Σ a·(b×c)|\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#Non-positive-cotan-weights-(star1)","page":"Geometry","title":"Non-positive cotan weights (star1)","text":"The cotan weight for edge (i j) shared by two triangles is\n\nw_ij = frac12(cotalpha_ij + cotbeta_ij)\n\nwhere alpha_ij and beta_ij are the angles opposite edge (ij) in the two adjacent triangles.\n\nFor an obtuse triangle, one angle exceeds pi2, making the cotangent negative.  If both opposite angles are obtuse (impossible for a valid triangle but possible after degenerate mesh operations), w_ij itself can be negative.  This does not break correctness of the Laplacian (which remains consistent) but can cause instabilities in transport schemes that rely on w_ij  0.\n\nDiagnostic:\n\nreport = star1_sign_report(dec)\n# report.n_nonpositive   number of negative entries\n# report.frac_nonpositive  fraction\n# report.min_entry       most negative entry\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"03_geometry/#See-also","page":"Geometry","title":"See also","text":"Mesh types\nDiscrete exterior calculus — how dual areas enter star_0\nCurvature — uses dual areas as denominators","category":"section"},{"location":"02_surface_diffusion/#Tutorial-2:-Surface-Diffusion","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Tutorial 2: Surface Diffusion","text":"This tutorial solves the heat equation on the sphere:\n\nfracpartial upartial t = mu Delta_Gamma u\n\nusing backward Euler (first order) and Crank–Nicolson (second order) time integration.","category":"section"},{"location":"02_surface_diffusion/#Setup","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Setup","text":"using FrontIntrinsicOps\n\nR    = 1.0\nmesh = generate_icosphere(R, 4)   # ~2562 vertices\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)\n\nnv  = length(mesh.points)\nμ   = 0.1    # diffusion coefficient\ndt  = 0.01   # time step\nT   = 1.0    # final time","category":"section"},{"location":"02_surface_diffusion/#Initial-condition","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Initial condition","text":"Use the first spherical harmonic u_0 = z  R (eigenfunction of Delta_Gamma with eigenvalue lambda_1 = 2R^2):\n\nu = [p[3] / R for p in mesh.points]   # u₀ = z (ℓ=1 mode)\n\nExact solution: u(t) = e^-mu lambda_1 t u_0 = e^-2mu t u_0.","category":"section"},{"location":"02_surface_diffusion/#Backward-Euler-(first-order-accurate)","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Backward Euler (first-order accurate)","text":"# First step: builds and factorises the system matrix\nu_be, fac = step_surface_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ)\n\n# Subsequent steps: reuse factorisation (no re-assembly)\nN_steps = round(Int, T / dt)\nfor _ in 2:N_steps\n    u_be, _ = step_surface_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u_be, dt, μ;\n                                                     factorization=fac)\nend","category":"section"},{"location":"02_surface_diffusion/#Crank–Nicolson-(second-order-accurate)","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Crank–Nicolson (second-order accurate)","text":"u_cn = copy(u)\nu_cn, fac_cn = step_surface_diffusion_crank_nicolson(mesh, geom, dec, u_cn, dt, μ)\n\nfor _ in 2:N_steps\n    u_cn, _ = step_surface_diffusion_crank_nicolson(mesh, geom, dec, u_cn, dt, μ;\n                                                      factorization=fac_cn)\nend","category":"section"},{"location":"02_surface_diffusion/#Error-analysis","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Error analysis","text":"# Exact solution at t = T\nu_exact = exp(-2 * μ * T) .* [p[3] / R for p in mesh.points]\n\n# L∞ errors\nerr_be = maximum(abs, u_be .- u_exact)\nerr_cn = maximum(abs, u_cn .- u_exact)\n\nprintln(\"Backward Euler error:   $err_be\")\nprintln(\"Crank–Nicolson error:  $err_cn\")\n\nExpected results (level-4 icosphere, mu = 01, dt = 001, T = 1):\n\nMethod L^infty error Order\nBackward Euler sim 5 times 10^-3 O(dt)\nCrank–Nicolson sim 5 times 10^-5 O(dt^2)","category":"section"},{"location":"02_surface_diffusion/#Using-the-cache-for-performance","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Using the cache for performance","text":"For long simulations, the SurfacePDECache avoids any re-assembly overhead:\n\ncache = build_pde_cache(mesh, geom, dec; μ=μ, dt=dt, θ=1.0)\nu     = [p[3] / R for p in mesh.points]\n\nfor _ in 1:N_steps\n    step_diffusion_cached!(u, cache)\nend\n\nThe cache is built once (includes factorization) and reused at zero marginal allocation cost per step.","category":"section"},{"location":"02_surface_diffusion/#Poisson-solve-(steady-state)","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Poisson solve (steady state)","text":"For the Poisson equation -Delta_Gamma u = f on the sphere with a compatible source f:\n\n# Source: f = 6z (eigenfunction with eigenvalue 6/R² for ℓ=2)\nf = [6 * p[3] for p in mesh.points]\nenforce_compatibility!(f, mesh, geom)   # ensure ∫ f dA = 0\n\nu_poisson = solve_surface_poisson(mesh, geom, dec, f)\nprintln(\"Poisson residual: \", maximum(abs, dec.laplacian * u_poisson .- f))","category":"section"},{"location":"02_surface_diffusion/#See-also","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"See also","text":"Getting started\nReaction–diffusion tutorial\nMath: Surface diffusion\nAPI: PDE solvers","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Plotting-with-Makie","page":"Plotting with Makie","title":"Plotting with Makie","text":"FrontIntrinsicOps.jl provides an optional Makie extension for plotting raw front meshes (CurveMesh, SurfaceMesh) and geometry overlays.\n\nPlotting is activated when a Makie backend is loaded, for example:\n\nusing CairoMakie\nusing FrontIntrinsicOps","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Theme","page":"Plotting with Makie","title":"Theme","text":"set_makie_theme!()\n\nThis applies a lightweight publication-oriented style used across examples.","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Curve-plotting","page":"Plotting with Makie","title":"Curve plotting","text":"mesh = sample_circle(1.0, 128)\nfig, ax, p = plot_front(mesh; show_vertices=true, title=\"curve\")\nsave(\"curve.png\", fig)","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Surface-plotting","page":"Plotting with Makie","title":"Surface plotting","text":"mesh = generate_icosphere(1.0, 2)\nfig, ax, p = plot_front(mesh; wireframe=true, transparency=true, alpha=0.9)\nsave(\"surface.png\", fig)","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Normals-overlay","page":"Plotting with Makie","title":"Normals overlay","text":"geom = compute_geometry(mesh)\nfig, ax, p = plot_front(mesh)\nplot_normals(mesh, geom; figure=fig, axis=ax, scale=0.05, every=8)\nsave(\"normals.png\", fig)","category":"section"},{"location":"plotting/#Convenience-behavior","page":"Plotting with Makie","title":"Convenience behavior","text":"The extension defines Makie conversions for mesh types, so these also work:\n\nfig = plot(sample_circle(1.0, 64))\nfig = plot(generate_icosphere(1.0, 1))\n\nIf Makie is not loaded, plotting functions throw a clear error explaining how to enable a backend.","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Scalar-Transport-on-Surfaces","page":"Transport","title":"Scalar Transport on Surfaces","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Overview","page":"Transport","title":"Overview","text":"FrontIntrinsicOps.jl implements conservative scalar transport on triangulated surfaces.  The key design choices are:\n\nA DEC-consistent edge-flux formula using cotan weights.\nThree explicit time integrators: Forward Euler, SSP-RK2, SSP-RK3.\nTwo spatial schemes: upwind (1st order) and centered (2nd order).\nA CFL-based time-step estimator.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#The-transport-PDE","page":"Transport","title":"The transport PDE","text":"fracpartial upartial t + nabla_Gamma cdot (v u) = 0 quad (x t) in Gamma times 0 T\n\nwhere v  Gamma to TGamma is a prescribed tangential velocity field and nabla_Gamma cdot is the surface divergence.\n\nConservation: On a closed surface int_Gamma u  dA is conserved provided nabla_Gamma cdot v = 0 (divergence-free velocity).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Tangential-projection","page":"Transport","title":"Tangential projection","text":"A velocity field v  V to mathbbR^3 given in ambient space is projected to the tangent plane at each vertex before use:\n\nv_i^tau = v_i - (v_i cdot hatn_i) hatn_i\n\nvel_tang = tangential_projection(mesh, geom, vel)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Edge-flux-velocity","page":"Transport","title":"Edge-flux velocity","text":"The scalar flux through each edge is computed from the vertex velocities. For edge e = (i j) with unit tangent hatt_e:\n\nv_e = fracv_i + v_j2 cdot hatt_e\n\nThis is the average of the two vertex velocities projected onto the edge tangent direction.\n\nve = edge_flux_velocity(mesh, geom, vel)   # Vector{T}, length N_E\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Transport-operator-—-semi-discrete-form","page":"Transport","title":"Transport operator — semi-discrete form","text":"The semi-discrete equation is:\n\nM fracdudt + A u = 0\n\nwhere M = star_0 is the mass matrix and A is the transport operator assembled as a sparse N_V times N_V matrix.\n\nThe transport operator uses the DEC codifferential structure.  For each vertex i:\n\n(Au)_i = sum_e ni i sigma_ei cdot w_e cdot ell_e cdot v_e cdot u_e^textscheme\n\nwhere:\n\nsigma_ei in +1 -1\nis the incidence sign of d_0,\nw_e = frac12(cotalpha_e + cotbeta_e)\nis the ⋆₁ cotan weight,\nell_e\nis the primal edge length,\nv_e\nis the edge-flux velocity,\nu_e^textscheme\nis the upwinded or centered value on edge e.\n\nThe product w_e ell_e approximates the dual-edge length on a Voronoi dual mesh.  This makes the formula geometrically consistent with the Laplace–Beltrami operator.","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Upwind-scheme","page":"Transport","title":"Upwind scheme","text":"u_e^textup = begincases u_i  textif  v_e  0  u_j  textif  v_e  0 endcases\n\n(donor-cell value: upwind vertex supplies the flux)\n\nOrder: 1st order in h.\nNumerical diffusion: varepsilon_textnum approx v h  2.\nMonotone: no spurious oscillations.","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Centered-scheme","page":"Transport","title":"Centered scheme","text":"u_e^textcentered = fracu_i + u_j2\n\nOrder: 2nd order in h.\nNot monotone: can produce small oscillations near steep gradients.\n\nA = assemble_transport_operator(mesh, geom, vel; scheme=:upwind)   # or :centered\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#CFL-time-step-estimate","page":"Transport","title":"CFL time-step estimate","text":"The CFL condition for explicit time integration:\n\ndt leq C_textCFL cdot min_i fracA_i^*displaystylesum_e ni i w_e v_e ell_e\n\ndt = estimate_transport_dt(mesh, geom, vel; cfl=0.5)   # cfl ∈ (0, 1]\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Time-integrators","page":"Transport","title":"Time integrators","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Forward-Euler-(reference,-first-order)","page":"Transport","title":"Forward Euler (reference, first order)","text":"u^n+1 = u^n - dt M^-1 A u^n\n\nConditionally stable for dt leq dt_textCFL.  Not recommended for production; use SSP-RK2 or SSP-RK3 instead.\n\nu_new = step_surface_transport_forward_euler(mesh, geom, A, u, dt)","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#SSP-RK2-(Shu–Osher,-second-order-in-time)","page":"Transport","title":"SSP-RK2 (Shu–Osher, second order in time)","text":"u^(1) = u^n - dt M^-1 A u^n\n\nu^n+1 = frac12 u^n + frac12 u^(1) - fracdt2 M^-1 A u^(1)\n\nStrong-stability-preserving: All intermediate stages are convex combinations of Euler steps, so any monotone property preserved by Forward Euler is also preserved by SSP-RK2.\n\nu_new = step_surface_transport_ssprk2(mesh, geom, A, u, dt)","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#SSP-RK3-(Gottlieb–Shu,-third-order-in-time)","page":"Transport","title":"SSP-RK3 (Gottlieb–Shu, third order in time)","text":"u^(1) = u^n - dt M^-1 A u^n\n\nu^(2) = frac34 u^n + frac14 u^(1) - fracdt4 M^-1 A u^(1)\n\nu^n+1 = frac13 u^n + frac23 u^(2) - frac2dt3 M^-1 A u^(2)\n\nu_new = step_surface_transport_ssprk3(mesh, geom, A, u, dt)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Convergence-rates","page":"Transport","title":"Convergence rates","text":"On the unit sphere, transporting u_0(xyz) = z by the rigid-rotation velocity v = (-y x 0) for time T = 05:\n\nScheme Temporal Observed spatial O(h^p)\nUpwind + SSP-RK3 O(dt^3) p approx 1\nCentered + SSP-RK3 O(dt^3) p approx 2\n\nThe centered scheme matches the O(h^2) accuracy of the Laplace–Beltrami operator; the upwind scheme is limited to O(h^1) due to numerical diffusion.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#Mass-conservation","page":"Transport","title":"Mass conservation","text":"On a closed surface with a divergence-free velocity:\n\nfracddt int_Gamma u  dA = -int_Gamma nabla_Gamma cdot (vu)  dA = 0\n\nDiscrete conservation:\n\nfracddt mathbf1^top M u = -mathbf1^top A u = 0\n\nThis holds because mathbf1^top A = 0 for a conservative, divergence-free discrete operator.  Monitor conservation as:\n\nmass = sum(geom.vertex_dual_areas .* u)   # should be constant\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"08_transport/#See-also","page":"Transport","title":"See also","text":"Advection–diffusion IMEX\nHigh-resolution transport\nTangential vector calculus","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Curvature","page":"Curvature","title":"Curvature","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Overview","page":"Curvature","title":"Overview","text":"FrontIntrinsicOps.jl computes three types of discrete curvature:\n\nSigned curvature kappa — for polygonal curves in mathbbR^2.\nMean curvature H — for triangulated surfaces.\nGaussian curvature K — via the angle-defect formula.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Signed-curvature-of-a-polygonal-curve","page":"Curvature","title":"Signed curvature of a polygonal curve","text":"For a vertex v_i on a closed polygonal curve with adjacent edges e_i-1 = (v_i-1 v_i) and e_i = (v_i v_i+1):\n\nTurning angle:\n\ntheta_i = textsigned angle from  hatt_i-1 text to  hatt_i\n\nwhere hatt_e is the unit tangent of edge e.\n\nDiscrete signed curvature:\n\nkappa_i = fractheta_iell_i^*\n\nwhere ell_i^* = (ell_i-1 + ell_i)2 is the dual length at v_i.\n\nVerification (circle of radius R, N vertices):\n\nTotal length to 2pi R as N to infty.\nkappa_i to 1R\nfor all vertices.\n\nmesh = sample_circle(1.0, 128)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\nκ    = curvature(mesh, geom)    # ≈ 1.0 for unit circle\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Mean-curvature-of-a-triangulated-surface","page":"Curvature","title":"Mean curvature of a triangulated surface","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Mean-curvature-vector","page":"Curvature","title":"Mean-curvature vector","text":"The mean-curvature normal at vertex v_i is defined via the Laplace–Beltrami applied to the position vector:\n\nvecH_i = frac12 Delta_Gamma vecpbig_i = frac12 (Lvecp)_i\n\nwhere vecp = (p_x p_y p_z)^top is the vector of coordinate values and L is applied column-wise.\n\nDiscrete formula:\n\nvecH_i = frac12A_i^* sum_j in N(i) w_ij (p_i - p_j)\n\nThis is the cotangent-weight mean-curvature vector of Pinkall and Polthier (1993).","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Scalar-mean-curvature","page":"Curvature","title":"Scalar mean curvature","text":"H_i = vecH_i cdot mathrmsign(vecH_i cdot hatn_i)\n\nThe sign correction aligns the scalar mean curvature with the outward normal convention: H  0 for a convex surface (sphere), H  0 for a saddle.\n\nVerification (sphere of radius R):\n\nOn a sphere H = 1R at every point (principal curvatures kappa_1 = kappa_2 = 1R, H = (kappa_1 + kappa_2)2 = 1R).\n\nR    = 2.0\nmesh = generate_icosphere(R, 4)\ngeom = compute_geometry(mesh)\ndec  = build_dec(mesh, geom)\nH    = mean_curvature(mesh, geom, dec)\nprintln(maximum(abs, H .- 1/R))   # → 0 as mesh is refined","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Mean-curvature-normal-vector-field","page":"Curvature","title":"Mean-curvature normal vector field","text":"Hn = mean_curvature_normal(mesh, geom, dec)  # Vector{SVector{3,T}}\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Gaussian-curvature-—-angle-defect-formula","page":"Curvature","title":"Gaussian curvature — angle-defect formula","text":"The discrete Gaussian curvature at an interior vertex v_i is the angle defect normalised by the dual area:\n\nK_i = frac2pi - displaystylesum_f ni i theta_fiA_i^*\n\nwhere theta_fi is the interior angle of face f at vertex i.\n\nDerivation: On a smooth surface the Gauss–Bonnet theorem for a small disk of radius varepsilon around v_i gives\n\nint_textdisk K  dA approx K_i A_i^* = 2pi - text(sum of angles)\n\nThe formula uses this relation as a definition.\n\nVerification (sphere of radius R):\n\nK = 1R^2\n\nat every point; int_Gamma K  dA = 4pi for any radius.\n\nK     = gaussian_curvature(mesh, geom)\nintK  = integrated_gaussian_curvature(mesh, geom)   # Σ K_i A_i^*\nprintln(intK)   # ≈ 4π for sphere\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Gauss–Bonnet-theorem","page":"Curvature","title":"Gauss–Bonnet theorem","text":"For a closed orientable surface:\n\nint_Gamma K  dA = 2pi chi\n\nwhere chi = V - E + F is the Euler characteristic.\n\nSurface chi int K  dA\nSphere 2 4pi approx 12566\nTorus 0 0\nGenus-g surface 2 - 2g 2pi(2-2g)\n\nDiscrete identity: The angle-defect formula satisfies Gauss–Bonnet exactly (before floating-point rounding):\n\nsum_i=1^N_V K_i A_i^* = 2pichi\n\nResidual diagnostic:\n\ngb_res = gauss_bonnet_residual(mesh, geom)   # |∫K dA - 2π χ|\n# gb_res < 1e-12 on well-constructed meshes\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#Accessing-curvature-fields","page":"Curvature","title":"Accessing curvature fields","text":"geom_with_curv = compute_curvature(mesh, geom, dec)\n# geom_with_curv.mean_curvature    Vector{T}\n# geom_with_curv.gaussian_curvature Vector{T}\n\nOr directly:\n\nH  = mean_curvature(mesh, geom, dec)         # scalar mean curvature\nHn = mean_curvature_normal(mesh, geom, dec)  # mean-curvature vector\nK  = gaussian_curvature(mesh, geom)          # angle-defect Gaussian curvature\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#References","page":"Curvature","title":"References","text":"Pinkall, U. & Polthier, K. (1993). Computing discrete minimal surfaces and their conjugates. Experimental Mathematics 2(1):15–36.\nMeyer, M., Desbrun, M., Schröder, P., & Barr, A.H. (2003). Discrete differential-geometry operators for triangulated 2-manifolds. In Visualization and Mathematics III, pp. 35–57.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"06_curvature/#See-also","page":"Curvature","title":"See also","text":"Discrete geometry and dual areas\nLaplace–Beltrami operator","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Surface-Diffusion,-Poisson,-and-Helmholtz-Solvers","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Surface Diffusion, Poisson, and Helmholtz Solvers","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Overview","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Overview","text":"This module provides implicit time-integration schemes for the surface heat equation, the Poisson equation, and the Helmholtz equation on triangulated surfaces.  All solvers share the same Laplace–Beltrami matrix L and use sparse direct factorization (SuiteSparse / Julia's \\).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Mass-matrix","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Mass matrix","text":"The (lumped) mass matrix is the Hodge star star_0:\n\nM = star_0 = mathrmdiag(A_1^* A_2^* ldots A_N_V^*)\n\nM = mass_matrix(mesh, geom)         # diagonal sparse\nm = lumped_mass_vector(mesh, geom)  # just the diagonal vector\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Weighted-mean-and-compatibility","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Weighted mean and compatibility","text":"For the Poisson equation on a closed surface the right-hand side must satisfy the compatibility condition int_Gamma f  dA = 0.\n\nWeighted mean:\n\nbaru = fracsum_i u_i A_i^*sum_i A_i^*\n\nZero-mean projection:\n\nu leftarrow u - baru\n\nenforce_compatibility!(f, mesh, geom)    # ensures ∫ f dA = 0\nzero_mean_projection!(u, mesh, geom)     # subtracts mean\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Surface-Poisson-equation","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Surface Poisson equation","text":"-Delta_Gamma u = f quad Leftrightarrow quad L u = f\n\non a closed surface with the constraint int_Gamma u  dA = 0.\n\nSolvability: L is singular (constant nullspace) on a closed surface. Two regularisation strategies:\n\nTikhonov shift (gauge=:zero_mean, default): Solve (L + varepsilon I) u = f, then project u leftarrow u - baru.\nPin a DOF (gauge=:pin): Set u1 = 0 and solve the reduced system.\n\nu = solve_surface_poisson(mesh, geom, dec, f; gauge=:zero_mean, reg=1e-10)\n\nConvergence: Second-order in the mesh size h for smooth f and smooth surfaces (consistent with cotan-Laplace accuracy).\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Surface-Helmholtz-equation","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Surface Helmholtz equation","text":"(L + alpha M) u = f quad alpha  0\n\nFor alpha  0 the matrix is positive definite even on closed surfaces — no gauge is needed.\n\nu = solve_surface_helmholtz(mesh, geom, dec, f, α)\n\nUsage pattern: Helmholtz solves appear as the linear step in implicit diffusion, reaction–diffusion, and Hodge decomposition.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Heat-equation-—-Backward-Euler-(first-order)","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Heat equation — Backward Euler (first order)","text":"M fracdudt + mu L u = g(t)\n\nOne backward-Euler step (step size dt):\n\n(M + dtmuL) u^n+1 = M u^n + dt g^n\n\nwhich, after dividing by M (diagonal):\n\n(I + dtmuM^-1 L) u^n+1 = u^n + dt M^-1 g^n\n\nIn the implementation the unfactored form is used for better numerical conditioning.\n\nLocal truncation error: O(dt) in time. Stability: Unconditionally stable for all dt  0. Factorization reuse: The matrix (M + dtmuL) depends only on the constant parameters dt, mu.  Pass the factorization back to avoid repeated expensive factorizations:\n\nu, fac = step_surface_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ)\nfor _ in 2:100\n    u, _ = step_surface_diffusion_backward_euler(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ;\n                                                  factorization=fac)\nend\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Heat-equation-—-Crank–Nicolson-(second-order)","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Heat equation — Crank–Nicolson (second order)","text":"left(M + fracdtmu2 Lright) u^n+1 = left(M - fracdtmu2 Lright) u^n + dtbarg\n\nwhere barg = (g^n + g^n+1)2.\n\nLocal truncation error: O(dt^2) in time. Stability: A-stable (stable for all dt  0), but not L-stable (high-frequency modes are not damped in one step).\n\nu, fac = step_surface_diffusion_crank_nicolson(mesh, geom, dec, u, dt, μ)\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Convergence-rates","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Convergence rates","text":"On the unit sphere, decaying modes u(t) = e^-lambda t Y_ell^m (spherical harmonics of degree ell):\n\nMethod Time order Spatial order\nBackward Euler O(dt) O(h^2)\nCrank–Nicolson O(dt^2) O(h^2)\n\nBoth methods saturate at O(h^2) spatial error, consistent with the cotan Laplacian.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#Compatibility-of-the-RHS","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"Compatibility of the RHS","text":"When solving the Poisson equation Lu = f on a closed surface, the compatibility condition int_Gamma f  dA = 0 must hold.\n\nenforce_compatibility!(f, mesh, geom)   # modifies f in-place\nu = solve_surface_poisson(mesh, geom, dec, f)\n\nIf f does not satisfy compatibility, the Tikhonov-regularised system gives a solution polluted by a constant drift.\n\n","category":"section"},{"location":"07_surface_diffusion/#See-also","page":"Surface Diffusion","title":"See also","text":"Laplace–Beltrami operator\nReaction–diffusion IMEX\nCaching and performance\nOpen surfaces and BCs","category":"section"},{"location":"17_signed_distance/#Ambient-Signed-Distance","page":"Ambient Signed Distance","title":"Ambient Signed Distance","text":"This page documents the ambient signed-distance layer in FrontIntrinsicOps.jl.","category":"section"},{"location":"17_signed_distance/#Minimal-1-D-point-fronts","page":"Ambient Signed Distance","title":"Minimal 1-D point fronts","text":"In addition to ambient curve/surface queries, the package provides a minimal 1-D front primitive PointFront1D with exactly two supported configurations:\n\none marker xΓ,\ntwo markers (xL, xR) with xL < xR.\n\nSign convention matches the ambient API:\n\ninside: negative distance,\noutside: positive distance,\ninterface marker(s): zero.\n\nThe helper API is:\n\nsigned_distance(front::PointFront1D, x::Real)\nsigned_distance(front::PointFront1D, xs::AbstractVector)\nrebuild_signed_distance(front::PointFront1D, xnodes::AbstractVector)\ninterface_normals(front::PointFront1D)\n\ninterface_normals returns outward normal orientation(s) of the inside region:\n\none marker: [+1] (inside right) or [-1] (inside left),\ntwo markers: [-1, +1] (interval inside) or [+1, -1] (interval outside).\n\nThis 1-D support is intentionally lightweight and does not include 1-D DEC, 1-D PDE operators, or general 1-D graph topology machinery.","category":"section"},{"location":"17_signed_distance/#Problem-definition","page":"Ambient Signed Distance","title":"Problem definition","text":"Given a point q in mathbbR^N and a piecewise-linear front mesh Gamma_h:\n\n2D: polygonal curve (CurveMesh) made of oriented segments,\n3D: triangulated surface (SurfaceMesh) made of oriented triangles,\n\nthe distance magnitude is\n\n\nd(qGamma_h) = min_xinGamma_h lVert q-xrVert_2\n\n\nImplementation uses exact primitive kernels (segmenttriangle closest-point)\nand an AABB tree for acceleration but the returned nearest primitive and\ndistance match brute force up to floating-point roundoff\n\n Sign modes\n\nsigned_distance( sign_mode=) supports\n\n- unsigned always returns +d\n- pseudonormal oriented sign from the closest feature normal\n- winding global insideoutside sign for closed meshes only\n- auto winding on closed meshes pseudonormal on open meshes\n\nIf sign_mode=winding is requested on an open mesh an ArgumentError is\nthrown because insideoutside is not globally defined\n\nSupport summary\n\n Mesh type  pseudonormal  winding  unsigned  auto \n---------------------------------------------------------------\n Closed CurveMesh        winding \n Open CurveMesh    error    pseudonormal \n Closed SurfaceMesh        winding \n Open SurfaceMesh    error    pseudonormal \n\n Pseudonormal sign\n\nLet c be the closest point on the closest feature and n_ast the feature\nnormal (faceedgevertex pseudonormal) Then\n\n\nsigma = operatornamesignbig((q-c)cdot n_astbig)qquad\ns = sigma d\n\n\nThis mode is valid on both open and closed meshes\n\n- On closed meshes it is an oriented signed distance near the surface\n- On open meshes it is a **side-of-sheet  side-of-curve** sign not a global\n  occupancy classification\n- Points exactly on the front return zero distance\n- Near numerically ambiguous configurations if the signing dot-product is\n  within tolerance the sign can evaluate to zero\n\n Winding sign\n\nFor closed meshes only\n\n- 2D curves integer winding number test\n- 3D surfaces solid-angle winding number\n  w(q) = frac14pisum_fOmega_f(q)\n\nSign convention:\n\noutside Rightarrow +d,\ninside Rightarrow -d.\n\nWith package orientation conventions:\n\nclosed CCW curve in 2D: outside positive, inside negative,\noutward-oriented closed surface in 3D: outside positive, inside negative.","category":"section"},{"location":"17_signed_distance/#Public-API","page":"Ambient Signed Distance","title":"Public API","text":"cache = build_signed_distance_cache(mesh; leafsize=8)\n\nS, I, C, N = signed_distance(points, cache; sign_mode=:auto)\nr = signed_distance(point, cache; sign_mode=:auto)\n\nU = unsigned_distance(points, cache)\nw = winding_number(point, cache)\n\nSee examples/sdf_curve_closed_circle.jl, examples/sdf_curve_open_polyline.jl, examples/sdf_surface_closed_sphere.jl, and examples/sdf_surface_open_patch.jl.","category":"section"}]
}
